1
00:00:01,044 --> 00:00:04,004
[suspenseful music]

2
00:00:04,047 --> 00:00:06,354
♪

3
00:00:09,444 --> 00:00:12,403
[ominous music]

4
00:00:12,447 --> 00:00:19,454
♪

5
00:00:21,108 --> 00:00:23,980
- I think people are
fascinated by shark movies

6
00:00:24,024 --> 00:00:25,329
for two reasons.

7
00:00:25,373 --> 00:00:29,116
One, the shark is
a natural monster.

8
00:00:29,159 --> 00:00:32,119
But it's also the fact
that it's in the water

9
00:00:32,162 --> 00:00:33,772
and in the ocean.

10
00:00:33,816 --> 00:00:38,386
And I think the ocean has
great psychological effects.

11
00:00:38,429 --> 00:00:40,083
- When you go in diving,

12
00:00:40,127 --> 00:00:44,870
that moment into the ocean,

13
00:00:44,914 --> 00:00:47,612
and then you put your head down

14
00:00:47,656 --> 00:00:50,398
and you see the world
underneath you,

15
00:00:50,441 --> 00:00:52,487
and then you go down,

16
00:00:52,530 --> 00:00:55,055
and that moment of a dive
is this kind of

17
00:00:55,098 --> 00:00:58,580
going into this whole crazy,

18
00:00:58,623 --> 00:01:02,192
like, "what the fuck is down
there" other world.

19
00:01:02,236 --> 00:01:05,630
- The seafloor is
8,000 feet down.

20
00:01:05,674 --> 00:01:09,460
And we're thousands of miles
from anywhere.

21
00:01:09,504 --> 00:01:11,375
And you get in the water.

22
00:01:11,419 --> 00:01:14,857
And you look around you,
and it's dark everywhere.

23
00:01:14,900 --> 00:01:17,207
And your mind starts
to make up things.

24
00:01:17,251 --> 00:01:19,340
What's just out of sight
over there?

25
00:01:19,383 --> 00:01:20,819
And what's gonna get you?

26
00:01:20,863 --> 00:01:22,299
♪

27
00:01:22,343 --> 00:01:24,127
- That's the appeal
of horror movies in the water.

28
00:01:24,171 --> 00:01:25,302
That was the appeal of

29
00:01:25,346 --> 00:01:26,564
"The Creature
From the Black Lagoon,"

30
00:01:26,608 --> 00:01:28,000
the famous scene
where she's swimming,

31
00:01:28,044 --> 00:01:29,306
and the creature's swimming
under her,

32
00:01:29,350 --> 00:01:30,307
and she doesn't know it.

33
00:01:30,351 --> 00:01:32,092
And then it touches her leg,

34
00:01:32,135 --> 00:01:34,311
and she doesn't know
what it is.

35
00:01:34,355 --> 00:01:39,011
- It's one of the great kind
of fears and dramatic things,

36
00:01:39,055 --> 00:01:41,579
is being in the water
and something grabs you.

37
00:01:41,623 --> 00:01:43,886
I mean, the beginning
of "Jaws" just says it all.

38
00:01:43,929 --> 00:01:46,541
[woman gasping]

39
00:01:49,979 --> 00:01:52,938
[soft music]

40
00:01:52,982 --> 00:01:59,989
♪

41
00:02:01,469 --> 00:02:03,384
- I would define
sharksploitation

42
00:02:03,427 --> 00:02:05,908
as a genre of film

43
00:02:05,951 --> 00:02:08,432
or frankly any kind
of media portrayal

44
00:02:08,476 --> 00:02:10,217
that's about this idea
of the meta shark,

45
00:02:10,260 --> 00:02:14,090
which is constructing
a horrific, monstrous image

46
00:02:14,134 --> 00:02:16,527
of the shark
that is very loosely based

47
00:02:16,571 --> 00:02:18,660
in actual reality.

48
00:02:18,703 --> 00:02:21,880
It's that idea that we can
sort of stretch the truth

49
00:02:21,924 --> 00:02:23,491
and merge fact and fiction.

50
00:02:23,534 --> 00:02:25,188
- The classic
exploitation movies

51
00:02:25,232 --> 00:02:27,408
are T&A movies or gore movies,

52
00:02:27,451 --> 00:02:29,671
but there's many other kinds
of exploitation.

53
00:02:29,714 --> 00:02:33,892
Sharksploitation is a subgenre

54
00:02:33,936 --> 00:02:40,072
that capitalizes on
the popularity of shark mania.

55
00:02:40,116 --> 00:02:44,033
- It's rare
for the world to go,

56
00:02:44,076 --> 00:02:45,774
"We like this.

57
00:02:45,817 --> 00:02:47,123
We're interested in this."

58
00:02:47,167 --> 00:02:49,865
And because of that,
it's gotta be exploited.

59
00:02:49,908 --> 00:02:51,649
- And I think
what sharksploitation

60
00:02:51,693 --> 00:02:53,695
is really exploiting is "Jaws."

61
00:02:53,738 --> 00:02:55,610
And that's never died.

62
00:02:55,653 --> 00:02:57,177
People are still
doing that today,

63
00:02:57,220 --> 00:02:58,917
no matter how crazy
the premises get.

64
00:02:58,961 --> 00:03:00,223
[gunshot]

65
00:03:00,267 --> 00:03:01,877
- For these, like,
sharksploitation movies,

66
00:03:01,920 --> 00:03:03,574
whenever I see a title,
then I'm like,

67
00:03:03,618 --> 00:03:05,010
what the fuck is this gonna be?

68
00:03:05,054 --> 00:03:06,011
[laughs]

69
00:03:06,055 --> 00:03:07,012
You know you're gonna see

70
00:03:07,056 --> 00:03:08,057
something you've never seen.

71
00:03:08,100 --> 00:03:09,406
Like, "Sharktopus,"

72
00:03:09,450 --> 00:03:11,060
I've gotta see
what the sharktopus look like.

73
00:03:11,103 --> 00:03:13,584
I've gotta see what
its magical abilities are.

74
00:03:13,628 --> 00:03:15,804
I've gotta see
how it's gonna kill people.

75
00:03:16,892 --> 00:03:18,763
- It is not
a sharksploitation movie

76
00:03:18,807 --> 00:03:21,331
unless someone screams,
"Get out of the water."

77
00:03:21,375 --> 00:03:22,680
- Get out of the water!

78
00:03:22,724 --> 00:03:24,421
Everybody,
get out of the water!

79
00:03:24,465 --> 00:03:25,901
- Get out of the water
right now!

80
00:03:25,944 --> 00:03:27,816
- When I think of
sharksploitation,

81
00:03:27,859 --> 00:03:30,514
I think of sharks that defy
the laws of physics.

82
00:03:30,558 --> 00:03:32,603
And then the other thing
sharksploitation is doing,

83
00:03:32,647 --> 00:03:35,084
what it's exploiting,
is people's fear

84
00:03:35,127 --> 00:03:37,260
of being eaten by something
that they can't see.

85
00:03:37,304 --> 00:03:41,264
- I think there's just this
in-built fascination for us

86
00:03:41,308 --> 00:03:43,875
with, like,
this is a highly-evolved,

87
00:03:43,919 --> 00:03:45,312
deadly predator

88
00:03:45,355 --> 00:03:48,140
that we probably can't beat
in a fight.

89
00:03:48,184 --> 00:03:49,925
We can't outswim it.

90
00:03:49,968 --> 00:03:51,143
- We're frail.

91
00:03:51,187 --> 00:03:52,449
We don't have fins.

92
00:03:52,493 --> 00:03:54,495
We can't stay underwater
very long.

93
00:03:54,538 --> 00:03:56,845
We're fucked. [chuckles]

94
00:03:56,888 --> 00:03:58,847
We're shit out of luck, man.

95
00:03:58,890 --> 00:04:01,110
With all our stuff, we know
that naked in the water

96
00:04:01,153 --> 00:04:03,547
with that shark, man,
we're in trouble.

97
00:04:03,591 --> 00:04:05,854
So there's something
about that that reminds us

98
00:04:05,897 --> 00:04:08,117
of how frail we are,
vulnerable we are.

99
00:04:08,160 --> 00:04:10,554
And yet it ignites
something in us

100
00:04:10,598 --> 00:04:14,471
on the adrenaline level
that makes us feel alive.

101
00:04:14,515 --> 00:04:16,125
- Come on in the water!

102
00:04:16,168 --> 00:04:19,911
- When I first saw "Jaws,"
it completely blew my mind

103
00:04:19,955 --> 00:04:22,610
that, oh, my God, wait,
that could be in the water?

104
00:04:22,653 --> 00:04:25,003
- I was in that sweet spot age
when it came out

105
00:04:25,047 --> 00:04:26,483
where my parents
wouldn't let me see it.

106
00:04:26,527 --> 00:04:30,400
So one night with the cousins,
we snuck and saw it.

107
00:04:30,444 --> 00:04:31,445
And it terrified me.

108
00:04:31,488 --> 00:04:32,533
And my parents were right.

109
00:04:32,576 --> 00:04:34,317
- If I went into the bathtub

110
00:04:34,361 --> 00:04:36,232
and I couldn't see
below the bubbles,

111
00:04:36,276 --> 00:04:38,321
there was likely
a shark under there.

112
00:04:38,365 --> 00:04:40,976
And I couldn't take a bath
that night.

113
00:04:41,019 --> 00:04:42,456
- I mean, in the theater,
I felt like

114
00:04:42,499 --> 00:04:44,109
the shark was gonna come
under my theater seat

115
00:04:44,153 --> 00:04:45,502
and get me.

116
00:04:45,546 --> 00:04:46,764
I almost wanted to put
my feet up on the seat.

117
00:04:46,808 --> 00:04:48,549
That's how terrified I was.

118
00:04:48,592 --> 00:04:51,160
- That shot
from the bottom of the ocean

119
00:04:51,203 --> 00:04:53,293
of her just floating there,

120
00:04:53,336 --> 00:04:54,946
we immediately feel that

121
00:04:54,990 --> 00:04:57,775
that camera is something
watching her.

122
00:04:57,819 --> 00:05:01,388
And the idea that it has
all of this distance

123
00:05:01,431 --> 00:05:03,085
between her and it,

124
00:05:03,128 --> 00:05:05,479
that is pure thalassophobia.

125
00:05:05,522 --> 00:05:08,873
- A lot of fear of any
kind of oceanic monster

126
00:05:08,917 --> 00:05:11,006
comes from this idea
of thalassophobia,

127
00:05:11,049 --> 00:05:12,747
which is a real phobia
that exists

128
00:05:12,790 --> 00:05:15,445
where people are threatened
or scared

129
00:05:15,489 --> 00:05:17,186
of large bodies of water.

130
00:05:17,229 --> 00:05:20,189
So when you have something
like the shark come in,

131
00:05:20,232 --> 00:05:23,192
it contributes even more
to this fear.

132
00:05:23,235 --> 00:05:26,587
[woman screaming]

133
00:05:26,630 --> 00:05:29,111
- It really did make people
afraid to go in the water.

134
00:05:29,154 --> 00:05:30,504
And that's, I think,
another reason

135
00:05:30,547 --> 00:05:31,766
"Jaws" became so big.

136
00:05:31,809 --> 00:05:33,376
It's this elemental fear

137
00:05:33,420 --> 00:05:36,205
that people have had
for centuries, I guess.

138
00:05:36,248 --> 00:05:37,641
And this was the first movie

139
00:05:37,685 --> 00:05:39,774
to really make it
the central theme of the movie

140
00:05:39,817 --> 00:05:42,124
and really kind of exploit
that fear.

141
00:05:42,167 --> 00:05:44,344
Because everybody goes
swimming at some point.

142
00:05:44,387 --> 00:05:46,737
And it's taking an activity
everyone does

143
00:05:46,781 --> 00:05:48,913
and showing, you know,
the potential dark side

144
00:05:48,957 --> 00:05:52,439
and the horrible thing
that can happen to you.

145
00:05:52,482 --> 00:05:56,617
- Suddenly, society developed
this massive fear of sharks.

146
00:05:56,660 --> 00:05:59,750
And this idea that
the psychology becomes infused

147
00:05:59,794 --> 00:06:02,971
in an entire generation
and is still persisting

148
00:06:03,014 --> 00:06:05,756
that when we think about
why we are scared

149
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:08,411
when we're standing in
3 feet of water at the shore,

150
00:06:08,455 --> 00:06:09,847
it's because of "Jaws."

151
00:06:09,891 --> 00:06:11,762
What are you scared of? Sharks.

152
00:06:11,806 --> 00:06:14,374
And that's where we always go
first and foremost.

153
00:06:14,417 --> 00:06:16,114
And it did not exist
to quite the degree

154
00:06:16,158 --> 00:06:18,465
that we see it prior to "Jaws."

155
00:06:18,508 --> 00:06:20,423
- This is the first year
that I've come to the beach.

156
00:06:20,467 --> 00:06:22,817
And people have really
been upset.

157
00:06:22,860 --> 00:06:25,646
And they're really concerned
about the waters.

158
00:06:25,689 --> 00:06:26,908
A lot of people,
you talk to them.

159
00:06:26,951 --> 00:06:28,039
You say,
"Well, you been in the water?"

160
00:06:28,083 --> 00:06:29,780
And they say, "No."

161
00:06:29,824 --> 00:06:32,217
Just the water is beautiful,
it looks nice.

162
00:06:32,261 --> 00:06:34,089
But, you know, hey,
there's sharks out there.

163
00:06:34,132 --> 00:06:36,308
- I knew that as a child
I had dreamed

164
00:06:36,352 --> 00:06:37,788
about a maniac
that would attack me

165
00:06:37,832 --> 00:06:39,399
and cut off my head--

166
00:06:39,442 --> 00:06:42,010
an unreasonable thing
that you couldn't discuss with,

167
00:06:42,053 --> 00:06:43,446
you couldn't argue with.

168
00:06:43,490 --> 00:06:44,665
And I sort of thought
that people might

169
00:06:44,708 --> 00:06:46,231
react to sharks that way.

170
00:06:46,275 --> 00:06:49,583
- In the shark craze
which has gripped America,

171
00:06:49,626 --> 00:06:52,150
which Peter Benchley began
and others have added to,

172
00:06:52,194 --> 00:06:53,935
the search for objectivity
about sharks

173
00:06:53,978 --> 00:06:56,372
is a pretty discouraging
enterprise.

174
00:06:56,416 --> 00:06:59,941
- When you compare it to, like,
other subgenres of movies,

175
00:06:59,984 --> 00:07:02,378
like killer dog,
like "Cujo," for example,

176
00:07:02,422 --> 00:07:05,599
that didn't stop people
from buying dogs.

177
00:07:05,642 --> 00:07:08,036
But "Jaws" stopped people
from getting in boats,

178
00:07:08,079 --> 00:07:09,994
going in the water,
going in their pool,

179
00:07:10,038 --> 00:07:11,169
going in the bathtub.

180
00:07:11,213 --> 00:07:12,475
People who lived in Iowa
didn't want

181
00:07:12,519 --> 00:07:13,955
to get in the lake
near their house.

182
00:07:13,998 --> 00:07:15,957
It was just like
this phenomenon.

183
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:19,264
- And it became the movies
that changed the movies.

184
00:07:19,308 --> 00:07:21,789
- We had been making
low-budget

185
00:07:21,832 --> 00:07:23,486
science-fiction pictures,

186
00:07:23,530 --> 00:07:26,881
very often
underwater pictures.

187
00:07:26,924 --> 00:07:28,839
And when "Jaws" came out,

188
00:07:28,883 --> 00:07:30,885
"The New York Times" wrote,

189
00:07:30,928 --> 00:07:32,364
"What is 'Jaws'

190
00:07:32,408 --> 00:07:35,237
but a big-budget
Roger Corman film?"

191
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:38,414
He was right
in half of what he said.

192
00:07:38,458 --> 00:07:41,765
It was a big-budget
Roger Corman film.

193
00:07:41,809 --> 00:07:44,115
But it was also better.

194
00:07:44,159 --> 00:07:46,466
It was bigger and better.

195
00:07:46,509 --> 00:07:50,339
And I thought--and I talked
to a few of my friends--

196
00:07:50,382 --> 00:07:55,866
the major studios have caught
on to what we've been doing,

197
00:07:55,910 --> 00:07:57,999
and we are in trouble.

198
00:07:58,042 --> 00:07:59,957
But I was not the only one.

199
00:08:00,001 --> 00:08:02,699
There was a whole genre
of these

200
00:08:02,743 --> 00:08:04,571
underwater monster films.

201
00:08:04,614 --> 00:08:07,661
But they were all
low-budget films.

202
00:08:11,403 --> 00:08:13,144
- Many of the adventure movies

203
00:08:13,188 --> 00:08:16,234
of the 1920s and the 1930s

204
00:08:16,278 --> 00:08:17,627
took place at sea.

205
00:08:17,671 --> 00:08:21,936
A good example is
"The Sea Bat" from 1930,

206
00:08:21,979 --> 00:08:25,896
in which a giant manta ray
attacks sponge fishers

207
00:08:25,940 --> 00:08:27,768
near the West Indies.

208
00:08:27,811 --> 00:08:32,120
But for some reason, sharks
were considered less dangerous.

209
00:08:32,163 --> 00:08:33,643
- Back in the days,

210
00:08:33,687 --> 00:08:36,211
way, way back
from the start of humanity,

211
00:08:36,254 --> 00:08:40,084
people thought of sharks like
a "mysterical" creature,

212
00:08:40,128 --> 00:08:42,173
especially on
the small island

213
00:08:42,217 --> 00:08:44,349
and the Pacific Ocean.

214
00:08:44,393 --> 00:08:46,830
- Anyone who lived
in a coastal area

215
00:08:46,874 --> 00:08:49,920
who saw these creatures
in real life,

216
00:08:49,964 --> 00:08:51,792
we'd tell stories
about those things.

217
00:08:51,835 --> 00:08:54,316
So in mythology and folklore
in different places

218
00:08:54,359 --> 00:08:57,101
in the Caribbean,
in the Pacific,

219
00:08:57,145 --> 00:09:00,322
and in Africa have stories
of sharks.

220
00:09:00,365 --> 00:09:03,717
And oftentimes,
these sharks are neither

221
00:09:03,760 --> 00:09:05,066
malevolent or benevolent.

222
00:09:05,109 --> 00:09:06,633
They're somewhere in between.

223
00:09:06,676 --> 00:09:09,592
There are cases
where sharks actually

224
00:09:09,636 --> 00:09:11,333
are seen as ancestral spirits

225
00:09:11,376 --> 00:09:13,291
that might actually be helpful.

226
00:09:13,335 --> 00:09:16,599
And there are some folklore
stories where the sharks

227
00:09:16,643 --> 00:09:19,167
themselves actually
help people in the ocean

228
00:09:19,210 --> 00:09:21,082
rather than attack them.

229
00:09:21,125 --> 00:09:23,214
- In Greece, they actually
worshipped sharks

230
00:09:23,258 --> 00:09:24,738
and made it a shark god.

231
00:09:24,781 --> 00:09:29,394
But then, most of the shark
god wasn't an evil god.

232
00:09:29,438 --> 00:09:30,787
They didn't punish people.

233
00:09:30,831 --> 00:09:32,746
Very, very first shark movie,

234
00:09:32,789 --> 00:09:34,704
"Tabu" from 1931,

235
00:09:34,748 --> 00:09:35,966
the shark was godlike.

236
00:09:36,010 --> 00:09:37,272
It was a shark

237
00:09:37,315 --> 00:09:39,448
who protected an area
in the water.

238
00:09:39,491 --> 00:09:42,233
They actually made
the first rubber shark.

239
00:09:42,277 --> 00:09:46,847
But also, movies like
"She Gods of the Shark Reef"

240
00:09:46,890 --> 00:09:49,066
or "Omoo-Omoo, The Shark God"

241
00:09:49,110 --> 00:09:52,069
actually portrayed the shark
as a god.

242
00:09:52,113 --> 00:09:54,855
- And their belief in
the power of the shark god.

243
00:09:54,898 --> 00:09:57,945
- You would see
a statue of a shark.

244
00:09:57,988 --> 00:09:59,686
You would see movies
like "Tiger Shark"

245
00:09:59,729 --> 00:10:02,297
where you'd see the everyday
life of the fishermen.

246
00:10:02,340 --> 00:10:04,952
You'd see how hard it was
and how the shark was

247
00:10:04,995 --> 00:10:06,693
a big part of their lives--

248
00:10:06,736 --> 00:10:08,303
but not as a villain,

249
00:10:08,346 --> 00:10:10,784
but as an animal
they had to deal with.

250
00:10:10,827 --> 00:10:12,916
And they actually respected
the animal.

251
00:10:12,960 --> 00:10:15,789
- Now, these are all movies
with sharks in them,

252
00:10:15,832 --> 00:10:19,314
but they're not
"movies about sharks."

253
00:10:19,357 --> 00:10:23,405
- It was mainly just some
individual scenes with sharks.

254
00:10:23,448 --> 00:10:24,754
- Cause you're looking at me
like I'm--

255
00:10:24,798 --> 00:10:27,017
- There are even more
specific examples today,

256
00:10:27,061 --> 00:10:28,062
or in the modern period.

257
00:10:28,105 --> 00:10:29,063
- Shark head.

258
00:10:29,106 --> 00:10:30,325
This mission is cursed.

259
00:10:30,368 --> 00:10:32,283
- It's not cursed.

260
00:10:32,327 --> 00:10:33,328
- Shark head.

261
00:10:33,371 --> 00:10:35,112
- With DC and Suicide Squad,

262
00:10:35,156 --> 00:10:37,767
this idea of the half-human,
half-shark

263
00:10:37,811 --> 00:10:39,377
is becoming more popular.

264
00:10:39,421 --> 00:10:41,336
But it really has roots
in a mythology

265
00:10:41,379 --> 00:10:43,599
that is still very important
to people.

266
00:10:43,643 --> 00:10:45,819
There's this really,
I think, profound

267
00:10:45,862 --> 00:10:48,865
and deeply saddening scene
for a CGI character

268
00:10:48,909 --> 00:10:50,998
where he's standing
in an aquarium

269
00:10:51,041 --> 00:10:54,088
forlornly looking at these
other ocean creatures.

270
00:10:54,131 --> 00:10:57,178
And initially you're thinking,
of course, obvious metaphor,

271
00:10:57,221 --> 00:10:59,833
right, that he doesn't feel
like part of the human world.

272
00:10:59,876 --> 00:11:01,704
He misses part
of the ocean world.

273
00:11:01,748 --> 00:11:03,706
And then the tank breaks,

274
00:11:03,750 --> 00:11:05,577
and some of those
sea creatures

275
00:11:05,621 --> 00:11:07,449
start attacking him.

276
00:11:07,492 --> 00:11:10,757
It becomes this really quick,
but really interesting

277
00:11:10,800 --> 00:11:15,022
metaphor about not fitting in
in either world.

278
00:11:15,065 --> 00:11:16,588
- A king shark.

279
00:11:16,632 --> 00:11:17,720
- Bullshit.

280
00:11:17,764 --> 00:11:19,853
- What the fuck?

281
00:11:19,896 --> 00:11:22,420
- Some people claim that
Nanaue is a descendant

282
00:11:22,464 --> 00:11:24,161
of an ancient shark god.

283
00:11:24,205 --> 00:11:26,337
Whatever the case,
he's strong and deadly.

284
00:11:26,381 --> 00:11:29,384
- An interesting example
of sharks in mythology

285
00:11:29,427 --> 00:11:31,168
is the story of Nanaue,

286
00:11:31,212 --> 00:11:32,909
which comes from
the Hawaiian Islands.

287
00:11:32,953 --> 00:11:34,606
So there there's a king
of the sharks.

288
00:11:34,650 --> 00:11:38,698
And the king is a shark
who can shapeshift and sees

289
00:11:38,741 --> 00:11:43,093
a beautiful woman and decides
to shapeshift into a human man

290
00:11:43,137 --> 00:11:44,399
to sort of pursue her.

291
00:11:44,442 --> 00:11:45,835
They have an affair.

292
00:11:45,879 --> 00:11:50,057
And they have a child,
a boy who is a demigod.

293
00:11:50,100 --> 00:11:52,886
And he's born with the mouth
of a shark on his back.

294
00:11:52,929 --> 00:11:56,803
And Nanaue is eventually
killed because of the threat

295
00:11:56,846 --> 00:11:58,718
that he poses
to the other people.

296
00:11:58,761 --> 00:12:01,111
But Nanaue is a very
important figure

297
00:12:01,155 --> 00:12:03,897
in Hawaiian indigenous lore

298
00:12:03,940 --> 00:12:06,769
because of this association
with the king of sharks.

299
00:12:06,813 --> 00:12:08,771
And that seems like a really
interesting story to me.

300
00:12:08,815 --> 00:12:11,948
I think it's fascinating
that when Europeans and even

301
00:12:11,992 --> 00:12:14,777
cinematographers
in the 20th and 21st century

302
00:12:14,821 --> 00:12:16,823
started thinking
of shark monsters,

303
00:12:16,866 --> 00:12:18,781
instead of going
into the folklore,

304
00:12:18,825 --> 00:12:20,740
we looked at the real shark
again.

305
00:12:20,783 --> 00:12:23,699
And James Bond did contribute

306
00:12:23,743 --> 00:12:26,006
to this idea of sharks
as monstrous

307
00:12:26,049 --> 00:12:27,964
by associating them
with the villains

308
00:12:28,008 --> 00:12:30,053
of James Bond films.

309
00:12:30,097 --> 00:12:31,968
- Gently, my friend. Gently.

310
00:12:32,012 --> 00:12:36,233
- I got interested in shark
movies when I was a young kid.

311
00:12:36,277 --> 00:12:39,802
It was actually "Jaws,"
but not "Jaws," the movie.

312
00:12:39,846 --> 00:12:42,849
It was Jaws, the character
from "The Spy Who Loved Me."

313
00:12:42,892 --> 00:12:45,068
You know, the big guy
with the steel teeth.

314
00:12:45,112 --> 00:12:49,812
- And Jaws would kill people
not with his gigantic body

315
00:12:49,856 --> 00:12:51,814
and hands or a gun or a knife.

316
00:12:51,858 --> 00:12:54,643
He would go up to you
and bite you on the neck.

317
00:12:54,686 --> 00:12:57,820
And then he bites the shark
at the end.

318
00:12:57,864 --> 00:12:59,866
- In stuff like
"Live and Let Die"

319
00:12:59,909 --> 00:13:01,215
and "Thunderball,"

320
00:13:01,258 --> 00:13:03,826
we have James encountering,
you know,

321
00:13:03,870 --> 00:13:06,611
a shark in the ocean
that goes directly after him,

322
00:13:06,655 --> 00:13:09,049
and you know,
he has to fight it off.

323
00:13:09,092 --> 00:13:12,008
But more commonly, and I think
more interestingly,

324
00:13:12,052 --> 00:13:15,098
is sharks being used
as a form of execution,

325
00:13:15,142 --> 00:13:16,491
which to my knowledge
is something

326
00:13:16,534 --> 00:13:18,275
that never really occurred.

327
00:13:18,319 --> 00:13:20,190
But you have
these pits of sharks

328
00:13:20,234 --> 00:13:22,802
and you have these villains
who are cruelly

329
00:13:22,845 --> 00:13:25,500
throwing people into
these shark pits.

330
00:13:25,543 --> 00:13:27,458
And they're
instantly devoured.

331
00:13:27,502 --> 00:13:30,505
And there's plumes of blood
everywhere.

332
00:13:30,548 --> 00:13:33,856
- The villain in "Thunderball"
kept sharks in a pool

333
00:13:33,900 --> 00:13:35,466
on his island compound...

334
00:13:35,510 --> 00:13:36,685
- With sharks, no less.

335
00:13:36,728 --> 00:13:39,296
- Both as a way
to dispose of enemies

336
00:13:39,340 --> 00:13:41,472
and as a security measure
and just

337
00:13:41,516 --> 00:13:43,605
a signifier of being evil.

338
00:13:43,648 --> 00:13:46,434
In the first
"Despicable Me" movie,

339
00:13:46,477 --> 00:13:49,089
they had sharks in a pool too,
sort of as an homage to that.

340
00:13:50,917 --> 00:13:51,961
- Quiet down, fish.

341
00:13:52,005 --> 00:13:53,571
- And you know,
in "Austin Powers,"

342
00:13:53,615 --> 00:13:55,617
Dr. Evil wants sharks that have

343
00:13:55,660 --> 00:13:57,619
frickin' laser beams
on their heads.

344
00:13:57,662 --> 00:14:00,622
- Sharks with laser beams
attached to their heads.

345
00:14:00,665 --> 00:14:03,103
- The villain has sharks
in "The Phantom."

346
00:14:03,146 --> 00:14:05,583
- "Batman,"
the movie from the '60s,

347
00:14:05,627 --> 00:14:08,891
there's a very famous scene
where we see Batman

348
00:14:08,935 --> 00:14:10,110
struggling with a shark.

349
00:14:10,153 --> 00:14:11,981
He's hanging
beneath a helicopter,

350
00:14:12,025 --> 00:14:13,809
and a shark attacks him.

351
00:14:13,853 --> 00:14:16,768
It's very obviously
a rubber shark.

352
00:14:16,812 --> 00:14:18,901
And the only reason
it's moving

353
00:14:18,945 --> 00:14:21,556
is because Batman
is moving his leg.

354
00:14:21,599 --> 00:14:22,774
And he's reaching up
to the helicopter.

355
00:14:22,818 --> 00:14:24,254
And Robin's sitting there

356
00:14:24,298 --> 00:14:27,605
and he's asking for this
shark repellent bat spray.

357
00:14:27,649 --> 00:14:29,216
And he starts spraying
the shark

358
00:14:29,259 --> 00:14:31,479
and then it's releasing
its rubber teeth.

359
00:14:31,522 --> 00:14:32,915
And it's dropping down.

360
00:14:32,959 --> 00:14:35,483
That's an awesome scene.

361
00:14:35,526 --> 00:14:39,704
- An exploding shark
was pulling my leg.

362
00:14:39,748 --> 00:14:40,923
- The Joker!

363
00:14:40,967 --> 00:14:44,579
- It all adds up
to a sinister riddle.

364
00:14:44,622 --> 00:14:46,537
Riddle-er.

365
00:14:46,581 --> 00:14:48,061
Riddler?

366
00:14:48,104 --> 00:14:50,063
- Oh, a thought strikes me.

367
00:14:51,412 --> 00:14:54,850
- So sharks become associated
with being kept as pets

368
00:14:54,894 --> 00:14:58,288
by being controlled by humans,
and more specifically

369
00:14:58,332 --> 00:15:00,073
being controlled by villains.

370
00:15:00,116 --> 00:15:02,684
So it's really doubling down
on this idea

371
00:15:02,727 --> 00:15:05,078
that sharks themselves
are inherently bad

372
00:15:05,121 --> 00:15:08,559
or evil because they're being
used in an evil way

373
00:15:08,603 --> 00:15:10,866
by humans, which,
of course, begs the question

374
00:15:10,910 --> 00:15:14,261
of who are the real monsters
in that situation?

375
00:15:14,304 --> 00:15:18,395
- Pre-"Jaws," there was no
sharksploitation genre.

376
00:15:18,439 --> 00:15:20,832
But there was
a treasure-hunting genre.

377
00:15:20,876 --> 00:15:22,573
And a lot of them involved
a shark,

378
00:15:22,617 --> 00:15:25,141
because the treasure was in
a sunken ship or some sort

379
00:15:25,185 --> 00:15:28,492
of underwater area
that they needed to somehow

380
00:15:28,536 --> 00:15:31,887
get down to retrieve
the treasure.

381
00:15:31,931 --> 00:15:34,194
- If you take one
of the more interesting

382
00:15:34,237 --> 00:15:35,978
treasure hunt movies,
shark movies,

383
00:15:36,022 --> 00:15:37,414
it was a movie called "Shark!"

384
00:15:37,458 --> 00:15:40,243
with a big name actor,
Burt Reynolds.

385
00:15:40,287 --> 00:15:42,985
But the most interesting story
about that movie

386
00:15:43,029 --> 00:15:46,119
was actually the unfortunate
death of one of the stuntmen,

387
00:15:46,162 --> 00:15:48,077
because when they made
the movie,

388
00:15:48,121 --> 00:15:49,861
they made it with real sharks.

389
00:15:49,905 --> 00:15:52,212
And unfortunately,
one of the stuntmen

390
00:15:52,255 --> 00:15:53,996
got too close
to one of the sharks,

391
00:15:54,040 --> 00:15:57,260
and he actually died.

392
00:15:57,304 --> 00:16:00,307
- They had been shooting in
an area that was netted off,

393
00:16:00,350 --> 00:16:04,093
but the shark broke through
the netting right into the shot

394
00:16:04,137 --> 00:16:06,748
and killed the stuntman
right on camera.

395
00:16:06,791 --> 00:16:08,532
So that was bad enough.

396
00:16:08,576 --> 00:16:12,710
But the producers actually
included the footage

397
00:16:12,754 --> 00:16:17,280
of Jose's death in the film.

398
00:16:17,324 --> 00:16:21,545
They immediately started
publicizing that a stuntman

399
00:16:21,589 --> 00:16:26,594
was killed during the making of
this film to garner publicity.

400
00:16:26,637 --> 00:16:29,118
They sold the story
to "Life Magazine."

401
00:16:29,162 --> 00:16:31,773
They eventually changed
the name of the movie

402
00:16:31,816 --> 00:16:34,210
from "Caine" to "Shark!"

403
00:16:34,254 --> 00:16:38,301
Then when "Jaws" came out,
they re-released the movie

404
00:16:38,345 --> 00:16:40,782
to capitalize on it again

405
00:16:40,825 --> 00:16:42,784
and changed the title of it
to "Man-Eater."

406
00:16:42,827 --> 00:16:46,831
And so that is the dark side
of the term exploitation.

407
00:16:48,920 --> 00:16:51,053
- When you think about a movie
like "Blue Water White Death,"

408
00:16:51,097 --> 00:16:54,448
you can really villainize
a lot of what they did.

409
00:16:54,491 --> 00:16:56,493
But at the same time,
I think of it more like

410
00:16:56,537 --> 00:16:58,104
they were us, but at that time.

411
00:16:58,147 --> 00:17:00,497
And there was a lot
of real thought

412
00:17:00,541 --> 00:17:04,153
that these were very, very
dangerous, villainous animals.

413
00:17:04,197 --> 00:17:07,765
- We're looking for the animal
that I think is considered

414
00:17:07,809 --> 00:17:10,986
to be the most
dangerous predator

415
00:17:11,030 --> 00:17:12,466
still living in the world,

416
00:17:12,509 --> 00:17:16,296
the great white shark,
which attacks the...

417
00:17:16,339 --> 00:17:18,167
- "Blue Water, White Death,"
you know,

418
00:17:18,211 --> 00:17:20,517
I missed that
when it first came out.

419
00:17:20,561 --> 00:17:23,738
But it became a--almost like

420
00:17:23,781 --> 00:17:25,653
the Dead Sea Scroll
or something.

421
00:17:25,696 --> 00:17:28,482
Those of us that knew the ocean
and knew sharks,

422
00:17:28,525 --> 00:17:30,397
when we saw it, we went, wow.

423
00:17:30,440 --> 00:17:31,963
That's really good.

424
00:17:32,007 --> 00:17:34,444
- Before this film,
there's only been one shot

425
00:17:34,488 --> 00:17:36,098
of a great white underwater.

426
00:17:36,142 --> 00:17:37,752
And that Ron Taylor had taken.

427
00:17:37,795 --> 00:17:39,536
And that was all there was.

428
00:17:39,580 --> 00:17:44,759
I was 24 years old
and I was just totally enamored

429
00:17:44,802 --> 00:17:46,978
of the idea of doing this.

430
00:17:47,022 --> 00:17:51,374
And then I met Peter Gimbel,
Stan Waterman.

431
00:17:51,418 --> 00:17:53,028
Jim Lipscomb I knew well.

432
00:17:53,072 --> 00:17:54,899
He was a great friend of ours.

433
00:17:54,943 --> 00:17:57,772
And then
Ron and Valerie Taylor.

434
00:17:57,815 --> 00:18:01,123
And these guys had
great delight in what

435
00:18:01,167 --> 00:18:05,345
they were doing and yet
were afraid in the sense

436
00:18:05,388 --> 00:18:06,650
it was unknown.

437
00:18:06,694 --> 00:18:09,436
Didn't know
what was gonna happen.

438
00:18:09,479 --> 00:18:11,742
Peter Gimbel invented
the cages.

439
00:18:11,786 --> 00:18:14,441
And that allowed them
to film underwater.

440
00:18:14,484 --> 00:18:17,183
And that was radical
at that time.

441
00:18:17,226 --> 00:18:20,708
And then they filmed
at night underwater,

442
00:18:20,751 --> 00:18:23,711
which was the scariest thing
in the world.

443
00:18:23,754 --> 00:18:27,149
It was a real, real danger
there, you know.

444
00:18:27,193 --> 00:18:29,543
And when they decided
to swim with the sharks,

445
00:18:29,586 --> 00:18:31,022
one of the things
they decided was

446
00:18:31,066 --> 00:18:32,676
they'd have these bang sticks.

447
00:18:32,720 --> 00:18:35,157
And so one person was filming,

448
00:18:35,201 --> 00:18:37,333
and then the other person
would be behind

449
00:18:37,377 --> 00:18:39,030
just looking for sharks
and trying to--

450
00:18:39,074 --> 00:18:40,771
but when you have goggles
like this,

451
00:18:40,815 --> 00:18:42,077
you've got no
peripheral vision.

452
00:18:42,121 --> 00:18:43,687
What's happening back there?

453
00:18:43,731 --> 00:18:44,775
What's happening over there?

454
00:18:44,819 --> 00:18:46,212
And the sharks would come up.

455
00:18:46,255 --> 00:18:47,691
And what they would do
a lot of times

456
00:18:47,735 --> 00:18:49,519
is the ocean tip, white tips,
would come up

457
00:18:49,563 --> 00:18:51,913
and bang it like this,
you know,

458
00:18:51,956 --> 00:18:55,090
luckily, instead of biting,
you know.

459
00:18:55,134 --> 00:18:57,484
- In the filming
of "Blue Water, White Death,"

460
00:18:57,527 --> 00:19:00,051
the filmmakers themselves kill
a shark in it

461
00:19:00,095 --> 00:19:01,444
because they get scared of it

462
00:19:01,488 --> 00:19:03,185
and they have their boom stick,
and they use it.

463
00:19:03,229 --> 00:19:06,406
And so I mention the movie

464
00:19:06,449 --> 00:19:08,625
not to make light of some
of those darker parts,

465
00:19:08,669 --> 00:19:10,584
but just to show people
all of these things

466
00:19:10,627 --> 00:19:12,151
are like dominoes.

467
00:19:15,632 --> 00:19:17,547
- The 18th century,
we start to see

468
00:19:17,591 --> 00:19:20,637
more negative illustrations
and paintings

469
00:19:20,681 --> 00:19:23,205
of sharks attacking people.

470
00:19:23,249 --> 00:19:25,425
At first, this is
usually sharks following

471
00:19:25,468 --> 00:19:28,515
alongside slave ships.

472
00:19:28,558 --> 00:19:32,214
And then in the 19th century,
when we see an increase

473
00:19:32,258 --> 00:19:35,913
in print culture, we start
seeing more shark attack

474
00:19:35,957 --> 00:19:37,959
encounters being
reported as well,

475
00:19:38,002 --> 00:19:42,616
one of which was a cabin boy
fell off the side of a ship

476
00:19:42,659 --> 00:19:46,446
in Cuba and his leg
was bitten off by a shark,

477
00:19:46,489 --> 00:19:49,318
which, of course,
newspapers latched on to.

478
00:19:49,362 --> 00:19:51,668
And that inspired
an American painter

479
00:19:51,712 --> 00:19:54,584
to make a very famous painting
called "Watson and the Shark"

480
00:19:54,628 --> 00:19:56,804
that depicts an exaggerated
account of that.

481
00:19:56,847 --> 00:19:58,806
And "Watson and the Shark,"
I do think,

482
00:19:58,849 --> 00:20:00,547
started some of these
negative depictions

483
00:20:00,590 --> 00:20:03,767
that have continued
throughout history.

484
00:20:03,811 --> 00:20:05,813
- In the real world,
there was two

485
00:20:05,856 --> 00:20:08,381
major events
which actually transformed

486
00:20:08,424 --> 00:20:09,947
the public's view of sharks.

487
00:20:09,991 --> 00:20:13,255
You had an event in 1916
in New Jersey

488
00:20:13,299 --> 00:20:16,476
where actually some
bull sharks swam up a river

489
00:20:16,519 --> 00:20:20,610
and attacked a few who I guess
was in the water swimming.

490
00:20:20,654 --> 00:20:23,004
And at that time in 1916,

491
00:20:23,047 --> 00:20:25,006
you didn't have
very much television.

492
00:20:25,049 --> 00:20:27,922
You have some radio and you
have some of the newspapers,

493
00:20:27,965 --> 00:20:30,359
so that story
about the shark attack

494
00:20:30,403 --> 00:20:33,841
traveled slowly but steadily
through all of America.

495
00:20:33,884 --> 00:20:36,104
And people was totally afraid
of sharks.

496
00:20:36,147 --> 00:20:39,673
You can see that the tourists
was running away

497
00:20:39,716 --> 00:20:41,501
from the beaches
because of when they saw

498
00:20:41,544 --> 00:20:42,980
the stories in the newspapers.

499
00:20:43,024 --> 00:20:46,636
- So we start seeing
front page newspapers

500
00:20:46,680 --> 00:20:50,074
with photos of sharks
and, like, "man-eater."

501
00:20:50,118 --> 00:20:52,033
So we have man-eater
associated with the shark

502
00:20:52,076 --> 00:20:53,469
for the first time.

503
00:20:53,513 --> 00:20:54,992
That's on one side
of the world.

504
00:20:55,036 --> 00:20:56,298
On the other side of the globe,

505
00:20:56,342 --> 00:20:58,648
Australia was getting
more into surfing.

506
00:20:58,692 --> 00:21:01,564
So of course, people
were also being attacked

507
00:21:01,608 --> 00:21:03,218
or bitten by sharks
in Australia.

508
00:21:03,262 --> 00:21:06,090
So as that circulated
through the globe,

509
00:21:06,134 --> 00:21:09,311
this idea of the man-eater
plus real shark attacks,

510
00:21:09,355 --> 00:21:11,574
the demonization
and the creation

511
00:21:11,618 --> 00:21:13,620
of the monster shark
really started becoming

512
00:21:13,663 --> 00:21:14,925
more and more prevalent.

513
00:21:14,969 --> 00:21:17,580
- And then throughout
the Second World War,

514
00:21:17,624 --> 00:21:21,018
you had the warship,
the USS "Indianapolis."

515
00:21:21,062 --> 00:21:23,934
The ship was carrying some
part of the atomic bomb

516
00:21:23,978 --> 00:21:26,720
that went down on Japan
in the ending

517
00:21:26,763 --> 00:21:28,330
of the Second World War.

518
00:21:28,374 --> 00:21:33,030
And on the way back,
a Japanese submarine

519
00:21:33,074 --> 00:21:36,904
sank the big warship.

520
00:21:36,947 --> 00:21:40,690
- Here you have Captain McVay
bringing the secret cargo.

521
00:21:40,734 --> 00:21:44,651
Intercepted by a Japanese sub,
sunk.

522
00:21:44,694 --> 00:21:51,353
So 1,200 men go into the water
and 300 and something survive.

523
00:21:51,397 --> 00:21:53,573
And many of them--
most of them, in fact--

524
00:21:53,616 --> 00:21:56,880
die from shark attacks.

525
00:21:56,924 --> 00:21:58,926
- Woody James was one
of the survivors

526
00:21:58,969 --> 00:22:00,580
of the "Indianapolis."

527
00:22:00,623 --> 00:22:02,146
And I got to ask him.

528
00:22:02,190 --> 00:22:04,801
I said, how did you feel
the first time you saw "Jaws"?

529
00:22:04,845 --> 00:22:06,847
Because that was
the first time anybody

530
00:22:06,890 --> 00:22:08,588
had ever heard about that.

531
00:22:08,631 --> 00:22:09,937
And he one of the survivors.

532
00:22:09,980 --> 00:22:11,199
And he said
he was just stunned,

533
00:22:11,242 --> 00:22:12,766
because these guys--
this was a generation

534
00:22:12,809 --> 00:22:14,202
that didn't talk about
these things.

535
00:22:14,245 --> 00:22:16,030
No one, none of their families,
none of the kids,

536
00:22:16,073 --> 00:22:17,597
no one really knew
what they went through.

537
00:22:17,640 --> 00:22:21,905
They just kept quiet
and buried that trauma.

538
00:22:26,997 --> 00:22:31,915
- Peter had many ideas
for novels.

539
00:22:31,959 --> 00:22:33,439
But the one he liked the best

540
00:22:33,482 --> 00:22:37,530
came from reading
about an article

541
00:22:37,573 --> 00:22:39,662
about a giant
great white shark.

542
00:22:39,706 --> 00:22:43,405
- In 1964, long before all
of this drama had happened,

543
00:22:43,449 --> 00:22:45,886
I read a story
in the "New York Daily News"

544
00:22:45,929 --> 00:22:47,540
about a fisherman
who had caught

545
00:22:47,583 --> 00:22:51,413
a 4,550-pound great white shark

546
00:22:51,457 --> 00:22:53,546
off the beaches of Long Island.

547
00:22:53,589 --> 00:22:56,592
And I thought, my God,
what would happen

548
00:22:56,636 --> 00:22:59,421
if one of those things came
into a resort community

549
00:22:59,465 --> 00:23:00,466
and wouldn't go away?

550
00:23:00,509 --> 00:23:02,293
- Peter wrote "Jaws."

551
00:23:02,337 --> 00:23:06,428
It was fiction based on fact,
I remember he used to say.

552
00:23:06,472 --> 00:23:11,215
So everything in it
could have happened

553
00:23:11,259 --> 00:23:15,219
or did happen, except this idea

554
00:23:15,263 --> 00:23:17,961
that the shark had
some idea to do it.

555
00:23:18,005 --> 00:23:21,661
- At that time, when Peter was
doing research for the book,

556
00:23:21,704 --> 00:23:23,445
there was not a lot
of research.

557
00:23:23,489 --> 00:23:26,622
But there was a theory called
the "rogue shark theory."

558
00:23:26,666 --> 00:23:30,844
And that was that once
a shark tasted human flesh,

559
00:23:30,887 --> 00:23:33,716
it would then hang around
and wanted more human flesh.

560
00:23:33,760 --> 00:23:35,936
Peter did not believe
in that theory.

561
00:23:35,979 --> 00:23:38,460
- Now, this shark
that swims alone.

562
00:23:38,504 --> 00:23:39,505
- Rogue.
- What's it called?

563
00:23:39,548 --> 00:23:41,898
- Rogue, rogue.
- Yeah.

564
00:23:41,942 --> 00:23:44,814
Now, this guy,
he keeps swimming around

565
00:23:44,858 --> 00:23:46,860
in a place
where the feeding is good

566
00:23:46,903 --> 00:23:48,818
until the food supply is gone,
right?

567
00:23:48,862 --> 00:23:50,472
- It's called territoriality.

568
00:23:50,516 --> 00:23:54,171
It's just a theory
that I happen to agree with.

569
00:23:54,215 --> 00:23:55,825
- The rogue shark theory
is nonsense.

570
00:23:55,869 --> 00:23:57,348
The idea that
one shark develops

571
00:23:57,392 --> 00:23:59,612
a taste for human blood
and then becomes evil

572
00:23:59,655 --> 00:24:01,352
and the only way
to save the beach

573
00:24:01,396 --> 00:24:03,267
is to track down that one
specific individual shark

574
00:24:03,311 --> 00:24:05,748
and kill it,
that theory has inspired

575
00:24:05,792 --> 00:24:08,185
a lot of what we call
shark control measures

576
00:24:08,229 --> 00:24:09,926
around the world,
and it doesn't work,

577
00:24:09,970 --> 00:24:12,189
because even if you could
identify what specific

578
00:24:12,233 --> 00:24:14,844
individual shark was
responsible for a given bite,

579
00:24:14,888 --> 00:24:17,368
which you almost certainly
cannot,

580
00:24:17,412 --> 00:24:18,457
you couldn't find it.

581
00:24:18,500 --> 00:24:20,110
And in the efforts to find it,

582
00:24:20,154 --> 00:24:21,547
you would kill
a bunch of other sharks

583
00:24:21,590 --> 00:24:24,593
that you're even saying
were not the ones involved.

584
00:24:24,637 --> 00:24:29,293
- Stephen really went with
the rogue shark theory.

585
00:24:29,337 --> 00:24:33,384
And it sure did make
for a really powerful movie.

586
00:24:33,428 --> 00:24:35,822
- The book's singular gimmick,

587
00:24:35,865 --> 00:24:39,347
which was to give you
the shark's point of view,

588
00:24:39,390 --> 00:24:41,567
that was, you know,
that was a first,

589
00:24:41,610 --> 00:24:45,179
to have the monster, you know,
as a character.

590
00:24:45,222 --> 00:24:48,443
- This is the shark
that was built for "Jaws 1."

591
00:24:48,487 --> 00:24:50,532
And it was built by a guy
named Joe Alves.

592
00:24:50,576 --> 00:24:52,752
He was one of Universal's
resident visual effect--

593
00:24:52,795 --> 00:24:53,883
special effects guys.

594
00:24:53,927 --> 00:24:55,058
Because there is a difference.

595
00:24:55,102 --> 00:24:56,625
Special effects are practical,

596
00:24:56,669 --> 00:24:58,322
visual effects are post.

597
00:24:58,366 --> 00:25:00,803
"Jaws," we did not have
visual effects to the scale

598
00:25:00,847 --> 00:25:03,589
where they could have done
this kind of shark things.

599
00:25:03,632 --> 00:25:05,504
Computers didn't exist
for doing CG.

600
00:25:05,547 --> 00:25:07,549
So they built this shark.

601
00:25:07,593 --> 00:25:10,683
Joe Alves and his crew
physically built this shark.

602
00:25:10,726 --> 00:25:13,555
And famously,
it did not work very well.

603
00:25:13,599 --> 00:25:16,340
So that is the reason "Jaws"
is such a powerful film.

604
00:25:16,384 --> 00:25:18,995
- It's actually those moments
in the movie that really

605
00:25:19,039 --> 00:25:21,650
separate it and make it
as good as it is,

606
00:25:21,694 --> 00:25:23,913
because it's such clever
filmmaking.

607
00:25:23,957 --> 00:25:26,829
- It's probably from where I
grew up in the '70s, watching,

608
00:25:26,873 --> 00:25:30,746
you know, movies
where the limitations

609
00:25:30,790 --> 00:25:33,532
from budget and maybe even
mechanical issues

610
00:25:33,575 --> 00:25:34,968
have limited the amount
of times

611
00:25:35,011 --> 00:25:36,360
you actually see the creature.

612
00:25:36,404 --> 00:25:38,798
And to me, that's much scarier.

613
00:25:38,841 --> 00:25:40,321
- Stephen King once said,
once you see

614
00:25:40,364 --> 00:25:42,366
the zipper down
the monster's back,

615
00:25:42,410 --> 00:25:43,672
the game's over.

616
00:25:43,716 --> 00:25:45,587
So the more real you can make
the situation,

617
00:25:45,631 --> 00:25:46,893
I think the more--
the easier it is

618
00:25:46,936 --> 00:25:48,590
for people to get
invested in it.

619
00:25:48,634 --> 00:25:52,463
- Our focus was creating
this creature

620
00:25:52,507 --> 00:25:55,510
as close as we could
to a shark.

621
00:25:55,554 --> 00:25:56,772
We weren't thinking about what

622
00:25:56,816 --> 00:25:58,252
he was gonna do to the future.

623
00:25:58,295 --> 00:26:00,776
- Summer wasn't for
blockbusters back then.

624
00:26:00,820 --> 00:26:02,865
It was just for
escapist fare, you know,

625
00:26:02,909 --> 00:26:04,998
drive-in movies,
that kind of stuff.

626
00:26:05,041 --> 00:26:07,435
That's the movie
that made $100 million.

627
00:26:07,478 --> 00:26:09,089
And everybody wanted
some of that.

628
00:26:09,132 --> 00:26:11,352
- When the movie came out,
everything went crazy.

629
00:26:11,395 --> 00:26:15,835
Everything totally changed--
not only for the shark movies,

630
00:26:15,878 --> 00:26:17,924
but also for
the cinema history.

631
00:26:17,967 --> 00:26:20,666
- Movies didn't open
in as many theaters

632
00:26:20,709 --> 00:26:22,450
then as they open in now.

633
00:26:22,493 --> 00:26:25,279
So I remember waiting
in line for five hours

634
00:26:25,322 --> 00:26:27,411
the first time we saw "Jaws,"
because we had to wait

635
00:26:27,455 --> 00:26:31,111
for two showings to come
and go before we got in.

636
00:26:31,154 --> 00:26:32,982
- At that time in 1975,

637
00:26:33,026 --> 00:26:34,810
the idea of running
your trailer

638
00:26:34,854 --> 00:26:37,726
as a TV commercial
was relatively new.

639
00:26:37,770 --> 00:26:39,685
And "Jaws" did it a lot.

640
00:26:39,728 --> 00:26:42,426
And that meant that
everybody was seeing it.

641
00:26:42,470 --> 00:26:44,907
It wasn't just
point-of-contact ads

642
00:26:44,951 --> 00:26:48,911
at the movie theater,
it was in your living room.

643
00:26:48,955 --> 00:26:50,391
- I saw those ads
all over the place.

644
00:26:50,434 --> 00:26:52,785
And it really stoked
my enthusiasm for it.

645
00:26:52,828 --> 00:26:55,048
The book was in every
bookstore you went into

646
00:26:55,091 --> 00:26:56,353
and supermarket.

647
00:26:56,397 --> 00:26:57,964
It was inescapable
during that summer.

648
00:26:58,007 --> 00:27:00,662
I think it was "TIME" magazine
had it on the cover.

649
00:27:00,706 --> 00:27:03,186
The cool thing was, even if
you couldn't see the movie,

650
00:27:03,230 --> 00:27:05,754
there was tons and tons
of merchandise.

651
00:27:05,798 --> 00:27:07,451
You know, that was one
of the first movies

652
00:27:07,495 --> 00:27:10,150
that got seriously marketed
with lots of tie-in stuff.

653
00:27:10,193 --> 00:27:13,022
So I had the "Jaws" game.

654
00:27:13,066 --> 00:27:14,023
- You're out.

655
00:27:14,067 --> 00:27:15,285
"Jaws."

656
00:27:15,329 --> 00:27:17,374
It's you against
the great white shark

657
00:27:17,418 --> 00:27:18,375
and each other.

658
00:27:18,419 --> 00:27:19,463
From Ideal.

659
00:27:19,507 --> 00:27:21,552
- Everybody wore
"Jaws" T-shirts.

660
00:27:21,596 --> 00:27:24,468
Everybody had "Jaws" posters
and toys.

661
00:27:24,512 --> 00:27:27,515
There was a parody song
released

662
00:27:27,558 --> 00:27:30,997
on top 40 radio
called "Mr. Jaws."

663
00:27:31,040 --> 00:27:33,260
And I just--
pardon the expression--

664
00:27:33,303 --> 00:27:35,001
ate that stuff up.

665
00:27:35,044 --> 00:27:36,872
To this day, the scene
that still scares me

666
00:27:36,916 --> 00:27:39,701
is when the fisherman's boat
gets capsized

667
00:27:39,745 --> 00:27:41,355
and there's
that overhead shot.

668
00:27:41,398 --> 00:27:43,966
And he's hanging on the boat
and you kind of see

669
00:27:44,010 --> 00:27:46,186
the shark come up
underneath him and grab him.

670
00:27:46,229 --> 00:27:48,971
- And the scene when you see
the shark for the first time

671
00:27:49,015 --> 00:27:51,060
in "Jaws,"
when he pop out of the water

672
00:27:51,104 --> 00:27:54,063
and we see Sheriff Brody
just floating, stalled.

673
00:27:54,107 --> 00:27:56,326
That was one of
the defining moments

674
00:27:56,370 --> 00:27:57,501
for shark movies for me.

675
00:27:57,545 --> 00:27:59,416
- Run down and chum
some of this shit.

676
00:28:01,723 --> 00:28:03,551
- That's another one
that still gets me

677
00:28:03,594 --> 00:28:04,987
every time I watch it.

678
00:28:05,031 --> 00:28:07,337
It's those classic moments
that just still work,

679
00:28:07,381 --> 00:28:09,339
no matter how many times
you've seen the film.

680
00:28:09,383 --> 00:28:12,691
- I remember seeing "Jaws"
and thinking how cool it was

681
00:28:12,734 --> 00:28:15,476
and how phony the shark was.
[laughing]

682
00:28:15,519 --> 00:28:17,739
You know,
after seeing the real things,

683
00:28:17,783 --> 00:28:21,700
but how great the cast was
and what a great film it was.

684
00:28:21,743 --> 00:28:23,876
And then I got worried,

685
00:28:23,919 --> 00:28:27,967
as a lot of people
who know sharks went, uh-oh.

686
00:28:28,010 --> 00:28:30,143
So if you make this
the great villains,

687
00:28:30,186 --> 00:28:32,232
then A,
they're gonna kill them.

688
00:28:32,275 --> 00:28:34,974
And B, people are gonna be
scared of them, and so--

689
00:28:35,017 --> 00:28:36,366
which is exactly what happened.

690
00:28:36,410 --> 00:28:39,892
- We were absolutely thrilled
with the success

691
00:28:39,935 --> 00:28:42,242
of the book and the movie
"Jaws."

692
00:28:42,285 --> 00:28:46,637
But we were just horrified
that people somehow

693
00:28:46,681 --> 00:28:49,423
felt that this was
a license to go out

694
00:28:49,466 --> 00:28:52,643
and kill every shark
they could.

695
00:28:52,687 --> 00:28:54,950
There were more shark
tournaments that were started

696
00:28:54,994 --> 00:28:57,300
to go out and kill sharks.

697
00:28:57,344 --> 00:28:59,563
- Around the time when
the movie "Jaws" came out,

698
00:28:59,607 --> 00:29:01,783
you can see
that shark landings

699
00:29:01,827 --> 00:29:03,959
really, really skyrocketed,

700
00:29:04,003 --> 00:29:05,744
specifically around that time.

701
00:29:05,787 --> 00:29:08,224
So specifically shark landings
around the United States.

702
00:29:08,268 --> 00:29:11,662
And that was because of
this very effective idea

703
00:29:11,706 --> 00:29:16,363
that people had, unfortunately,
that sharks were so dangerous

704
00:29:16,406 --> 00:29:19,409
that it was a safety issue
and that they were

705
00:29:19,453 --> 00:29:21,672
actually helping
by removing large amounts

706
00:29:21,716 --> 00:29:22,891
of sharks at one time.

707
00:29:22,935 --> 00:29:24,588
- Some species still
haven't recovered

708
00:29:24,632 --> 00:29:26,721
from that summer's
exploitation.

709
00:29:30,377 --> 00:29:32,509
- One of the very first
sharksploitation films

710
00:29:32,553 --> 00:29:35,034
that we see out of the gates
right after "Jaws" is

711
00:29:35,077 --> 00:29:36,818
"Mako, Jaws of Death,"

712
00:29:36,862 --> 00:29:39,255
which is
a William Grefé feature.

713
00:29:39,299 --> 00:29:42,345
It's an interesting film in
that it does use real sharks.

714
00:29:42,389 --> 00:29:44,957
And the actors
in the film are actually

715
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:47,263
swimming with real sharks.

716
00:29:47,307 --> 00:29:48,874
- I found out later that,
I think,

717
00:29:48,917 --> 00:29:50,963
some of the sharks had
had their teeth removed,

718
00:29:51,006 --> 00:29:52,921
which is kind of dubious.

719
00:29:52,965 --> 00:29:54,836
And I don't know
how I feel about that.

720
00:29:54,880 --> 00:29:57,143
But it is
a very entertaining movie.

721
00:29:57,186 --> 00:29:59,972
I'm also amused by the fact
that it's referred to

722
00:30:00,015 --> 00:30:02,322
sometimes as
"Mako, The Jaws of Death,"

723
00:30:02,365 --> 00:30:04,237
though I've never seen
a print of the movie

724
00:30:04,280 --> 00:30:05,847
or an ad or a poster for it

725
00:30:05,891 --> 00:30:07,588
saying,
"Mako, The Jaws of Death."

726
00:30:07,631 --> 00:30:09,111
And the sharks aren't makos.

727
00:30:09,155 --> 00:30:12,027
There are no mako sharks
anywhere in that film.

728
00:30:12,071 --> 00:30:14,073
- Unfortunately, some
of the tales coming out

729
00:30:14,116 --> 00:30:15,901
of "Mako, Jaws of Death"
is that the sharks

730
00:30:15,944 --> 00:30:18,817
were not treated very well
during the filming at all.

731
00:30:18,860 --> 00:30:21,254
Some of them were killed,
actually, for the filming.

732
00:30:21,297 --> 00:30:23,386
But what's unusual about it

733
00:30:23,430 --> 00:30:25,475
is one of the very few films

734
00:30:25,519 --> 00:30:27,042
that come out post-"Jaws"

735
00:30:27,086 --> 00:30:29,828
that is actually about
showing compassion to sharks.

736
00:30:29,871 --> 00:30:31,830
The movie itself
is about this man

737
00:30:31,873 --> 00:30:33,309
who is trying
to preserve sharks

738
00:30:33,353 --> 00:30:35,094
and is telepathically
connected to them.

739
00:30:35,137 --> 00:30:36,443
But at the same time,
you find out

740
00:30:36,486 --> 00:30:37,923
that some of
the filming procedures

741
00:30:37,966 --> 00:30:39,881
they were doing
to get these shots

742
00:30:39,925 --> 00:30:41,796
are really damn horrific.

743
00:30:41,840 --> 00:30:44,146
- Another shark movie
that is not afraid

744
00:30:44,190 --> 00:30:46,453
of killing any real sharks

745
00:30:46,496 --> 00:30:49,717
is "Sharks' Treasure"
from 1975,

746
00:30:49,760 --> 00:30:53,155
in which men go on
an underwater treasure hunt

747
00:30:53,199 --> 00:30:56,419
and they have to kill sharks
in order to stay alive.

748
00:30:56,463 --> 00:30:58,726
- And most of the trailer
is sharks getting killed,

749
00:30:58,769 --> 00:30:59,988
and really getting killed,

750
00:31:00,032 --> 00:31:02,904
like getting hit
with spears and bang sticks.

751
00:31:02,948 --> 00:31:04,601
And even at the time,
I'm like,

752
00:31:04,645 --> 00:31:07,517
they're killing sharks
on camera for this movie.

753
00:31:07,561 --> 00:31:09,084
"Tintorera" was another one

754
00:31:09,128 --> 00:31:10,651
that I caught up with
later on.

755
00:31:10,694 --> 00:31:13,741
That's like combining sharks
and sexploitation.

756
00:31:13,784 --> 00:31:15,612
You know, it's lots
of naked people, you know,

757
00:31:15,656 --> 00:31:16,918
and shark attacks.

758
00:31:16,962 --> 00:31:18,920
And that's a great example

759
00:31:18,964 --> 00:31:21,923
of exploitation at its finest.

760
00:31:21,967 --> 00:31:23,794
[woman screaming]

761
00:31:29,017 --> 00:31:31,367
[dramatic music]

762
00:31:31,411 --> 00:31:33,979
- I remember "Shark Kill,"
which is a TV movie.

763
00:31:34,022 --> 00:31:36,720
I think that was the first
kind of "Jaws" knockoff

764
00:31:36,764 --> 00:31:38,070
that made it to market.

765
00:31:38,113 --> 00:31:40,246
- They played it up
like it was "Jaws,"

766
00:31:40,289 --> 00:31:44,467
but it's about these two guys
that go out to hunt a shark.

767
00:31:44,511 --> 00:31:48,123
As a kid, it made me wonder,
is this what "Jaws" was?

768
00:31:48,167 --> 00:31:49,951
But it clearly wasn't.

769
00:31:49,995 --> 00:31:52,127
- And I remember
all the other TV spin-offs.

770
00:31:52,171 --> 00:31:54,477
Like Sheriff Lobo encountered
the shark.

771
00:31:54,521 --> 00:31:56,349
Like, all the Universal
TV series

772
00:31:56,392 --> 00:31:58,177
would have their characters

773
00:31:58,220 --> 00:32:00,266
encounter the shark
from "Jaws."

774
00:32:00,309 --> 00:32:03,269
- "The Hardy Boys" had
a shark episode.

775
00:32:03,312 --> 00:32:06,446
"The Bionic Woman" had
a shark episode.

776
00:32:06,489 --> 00:32:08,056
There's a show called
"Matt Houston"

777
00:32:08,100 --> 00:32:09,101
that had a shark episode.

778
00:32:09,144 --> 00:32:11,146
Sharks were everywhere.

779
00:32:11,190 --> 00:32:13,148
- There was Jabberjaw,
you know,

780
00:32:13,192 --> 00:32:15,150
the Scooby-Doo rip-off
of the talking shark.

781
00:32:15,194 --> 00:32:16,978
There was Misterjaw

782
00:32:17,022 --> 00:32:18,806
that was on
"The Pink Panther."

783
00:32:18,849 --> 00:32:21,287
And then I'll always remember,
they had the episode where

784
00:32:21,330 --> 00:32:24,638
the Six Million Dollar Man
fights a killer shark.

785
00:32:24,681 --> 00:32:27,989
- When he's holding
the shark and shaking it,

786
00:32:28,033 --> 00:32:29,425
it's the nurse shark,

787
00:32:29,469 --> 00:32:31,253
which is not
a dangerous shark.

788
00:32:31,297 --> 00:32:34,387
But when they're showing
the shark swimming away,

789
00:32:34,430 --> 00:32:36,302
that's a sand tiger.

790
00:32:36,345 --> 00:32:40,001
Now, a sand tiger,
doing that too?

791
00:32:40,045 --> 00:32:43,526
I think you'd be pretty stupid
to grab it

792
00:32:43,570 --> 00:32:45,485
and do the same thing
as you do with a nurse shark.

793
00:32:45,528 --> 00:32:47,052
- And then, of course,
you know,

794
00:32:47,095 --> 00:32:51,795
the most infamous example
is the jump the shark episode

795
00:32:51,839 --> 00:32:54,189
of "Happy Days."

796
00:32:54,233 --> 00:32:57,236
It has coined the idiom
jumping the shark,

797
00:32:57,279 --> 00:33:00,543
which is a term which means
that something has become

798
00:33:00,587 --> 00:33:03,198
so successful that there's
an inevitable point

799
00:33:03,242 --> 00:33:05,505
where that success
begins to sour.

800
00:33:05,548 --> 00:33:09,291
That moment is the moment
that it jumps the shark.

801
00:33:09,335 --> 00:33:10,814
- There he goes!

802
00:33:10,858 --> 00:33:13,208
- I mean,
Fonzie jumping the shark

803
00:33:13,252 --> 00:33:18,561
was the world going,

804
00:33:18,605 --> 00:33:20,955
"Yeah, it's just infecting
everything."

805
00:33:20,999 --> 00:33:23,088
Even Land Shark on "SNL,"

806
00:33:23,131 --> 00:33:24,263
you know, you hear the...

807
00:33:24,306 --> 00:33:25,264
♪ Dun-dun, dun-dun

808
00:33:25,307 --> 00:33:26,308
[woman screams]

809
00:33:26,352 --> 00:33:27,570
[laughter]

810
00:33:27,614 --> 00:33:30,747
It's like, already it's a bit.

811
00:33:30,791 --> 00:33:31,922
It's a joke.

812
00:33:31,966 --> 00:33:32,967
We know what's going on.

813
00:33:33,011 --> 00:33:36,318
There was--every comedy

814
00:33:36,362 --> 00:33:38,103
had a shark spoof

815
00:33:38,146 --> 00:33:39,582
where they would do the...

816
00:33:39,626 --> 00:33:41,106
♪ Bum-bum, bum-bum

817
00:33:41,149 --> 00:33:42,542
♪

818
00:33:42,585 --> 00:33:45,023
- "Caddyshack"
with the Baby Ruth bar.

819
00:33:45,066 --> 00:33:48,026
One of the "Police Academy"
movies.

820
00:33:48,069 --> 00:33:49,592
One of the "Clerks" movies.

821
00:33:49,636 --> 00:33:51,812
- ♪ Dun-nun, dun-nun
Salsa shark!

822
00:33:51,855 --> 00:33:53,161
We're gonna need a bigger boat.

823
00:33:53,205 --> 00:33:56,121
- And not only that,
it rippled into, like,

824
00:33:56,164 --> 00:33:58,732
movies like "Tremors"
and so many others.

825
00:33:58,775 --> 00:34:01,822
- It also changed
and actually introduced,

826
00:34:01,865 --> 00:34:06,479
like, a recipe for shark movies
and for disaster animal movies,

827
00:34:06,522 --> 00:34:09,612
animal attack movies.

828
00:34:09,656 --> 00:34:12,093
- One of the kind of
most unassuming

829
00:34:12,137 --> 00:34:15,314
sharksploitation movies didn't
even take place in the water.

830
00:34:15,357 --> 00:34:17,055
And that is "Grizzly."

831
00:34:17,098 --> 00:34:22,625
- Grizzly uses almost the exact
same script of "Jaws."

832
00:34:22,669 --> 00:34:25,280
- It uses a lot of the same
filming style,

833
00:34:25,324 --> 00:34:28,370
where it's POVs of it watching
people from a distance.

834
00:34:28,414 --> 00:34:30,546
It has a very similar tone
to it.

835
00:34:30,590 --> 00:34:33,332
And they actually used it
in the marketing campaign

836
00:34:33,375 --> 00:34:35,029
as well,
where it was something like,

837
00:34:35,073 --> 00:34:36,813
"Jaws" but on land.

838
00:34:36,857 --> 00:34:40,904
Like, it literally states
that it is taken from "Jaws."

839
00:34:40,948 --> 00:34:42,080
- Another one that was kind of

840
00:34:42,123 --> 00:34:43,820
a "Jaws" on land thing
was "The Car."

841
00:34:43,864 --> 00:34:46,171
You know, it's basically
a predator of sorts,

842
00:34:46,214 --> 00:34:48,608
you know, terrorizing a town,
from Universal.

843
00:34:48,651 --> 00:34:50,827
- And this car
just starts riding around,

844
00:34:50,871 --> 00:34:52,220
picking people off.

845
00:34:52,264 --> 00:34:55,832
And somehow the car feels
just like "Jaws."

846
00:34:55,876 --> 00:34:57,399
- In "Jaws,"

847
00:34:57,443 --> 00:34:59,662
"Jaws" kills a kid,
the little Kintner boy.

848
00:34:59,706 --> 00:35:01,882
In "Tentacles,"
they're gonna outdo "Jaws."

849
00:35:01,925 --> 00:35:03,623
They kill a baby
in a baby carriage.

850
00:35:03,666 --> 00:35:06,930
The tentacle pulls the baby
underwater, kills the baby.

851
00:35:06,974 --> 00:35:09,585
- Billy!

852
00:35:09,629 --> 00:35:13,023
- Two years after "Jaws"
comes out, we get "Orca."

853
00:35:13,067 --> 00:35:14,895
This is Dino De Laurentiis

854
00:35:14,938 --> 00:35:18,725
making a ridiculously
elegantly well-done

855
00:35:18,768 --> 00:35:20,335
exploitation film.

856
00:35:20,379 --> 00:35:22,642
- "Orca" was another one
that was kind of omnipresent.

857
00:35:22,685 --> 00:35:24,905
The poster, I think,
was on the back

858
00:35:24,948 --> 00:35:26,776
of every single
Marvel comic book

859
00:35:26,820 --> 00:35:29,083
that came out
in the summer of '77.

860
00:35:29,127 --> 00:35:30,824
So it's a big event film,
you know,

861
00:35:30,867 --> 00:35:33,261
even though it's obviously
just ripping off "Jaws."

862
00:35:33,305 --> 00:35:35,176
- So the way
that "Orca" is set up,

863
00:35:35,220 --> 00:35:36,612
it does this interesting thing

864
00:35:36,656 --> 00:35:39,659
where it puts the audience
on the side of the orca

865
00:35:39,702 --> 00:35:40,921
from the very get-go,

866
00:35:40,964 --> 00:35:43,837
because we start
with the killer shark

867
00:35:43,880 --> 00:35:45,230
kind of going
through the water,

868
00:35:45,273 --> 00:35:47,188
and we get the feeling
that that killer shark

869
00:35:47,232 --> 00:35:48,581
is about to eat somebody.

870
00:35:48,624 --> 00:35:50,191
And we think, okay,
it's like "Jaws."

871
00:35:50,235 --> 00:35:51,497
We're gonna be looking
at these killer sharks.

872
00:35:51,540 --> 00:35:53,499
- You think sharks are scary?

873
00:35:53,542 --> 00:35:56,066
What's bigger and faster?

874
00:35:56,110 --> 00:35:57,633
A killer whale.

875
00:35:57,677 --> 00:36:02,290
Orca shoots like a missile
and hits the shark,

876
00:36:02,334 --> 00:36:05,032
and the shark goes, wham,
out of the air.

877
00:36:05,075 --> 00:36:07,861
And Orca just kills the shark
because it wants to.

878
00:36:07,904 --> 00:36:09,210
- Jesus, what did that?

879
00:36:09,254 --> 00:36:10,864
- I think, out of all
the "Jaws" rip-offs,

880
00:36:10,907 --> 00:36:12,431
it is probably
the best crafted.

881
00:36:12,474 --> 00:36:15,999
[suspenseful music]

882
00:36:16,043 --> 00:36:19,089
- Roger Corman really had
an eye for trends.

883
00:36:19,133 --> 00:36:22,745
And he knew, in the '70s,
that it was a good idea

884
00:36:22,789 --> 00:36:24,834
to make "Jaws" rip-offs.

885
00:36:24,878 --> 00:36:27,228
- "Piranha" was
a reaction to "Jaws."

886
00:36:27,272 --> 00:36:30,753
We felt, all right,
they've gone up above us.

887
00:36:30,797 --> 00:36:33,800
We've got to raise our level
a little bit.

888
00:36:33,843 --> 00:36:35,149
- How could you not be aware

889
00:36:35,193 --> 00:36:36,324
you were making
a "Jaws" rip-off?

890
00:36:36,368 --> 00:36:37,891
I mean, it's a "Jaws" rip-off.

891
00:36:37,934 --> 00:36:39,675
I mean, obviously nobody
would be making this movie

892
00:36:39,719 --> 00:36:41,068
if it wasn't for the fact
that there had been

893
00:36:41,111 --> 00:36:42,809
a big hit movie
that took place

894
00:36:42,852 --> 00:36:44,506
underwater with a monster.

895
00:36:44,550 --> 00:36:49,946
And so it was--we were so
alert to the fact that it was

896
00:36:49,990 --> 00:36:52,819
a "Jaws" rip-off that the
opening titles of the movie

897
00:36:52,862 --> 00:36:55,256
have the heroine playing
a "Jaws" video game,

898
00:36:55,300 --> 00:36:57,476
as if to say, we get it.

899
00:36:57,519 --> 00:36:59,434
Just forget it. We know it.

900
00:36:59,478 --> 00:37:01,131
We know it's a rip-off.
You know.

901
00:37:01,175 --> 00:37:02,568
We know that you know.

902
00:37:02,611 --> 00:37:05,353
So just forget about it
and have a good time.

903
00:37:05,397 --> 00:37:09,270
- We shot the "Piranha" in
the USC swimming pool.

904
00:37:09,314 --> 00:37:14,275
And we had some fake blood
and one thing and another.

905
00:37:14,319 --> 00:37:17,452
And it sort of spread
throughout the swimming pool.

906
00:37:17,496 --> 00:37:21,978
And SC was not happy
with what we had done.

907
00:37:22,022 --> 00:37:24,285
- Whatever it is
that we did caused

908
00:37:24,329 --> 00:37:28,333
a fungus to grow
that ate away at the pool

909
00:37:28,376 --> 00:37:31,031
and started to eat--

910
00:37:31,074 --> 00:37:33,816
literally eat--
the paint off the pool.

911
00:37:33,860 --> 00:37:35,688
And so no one could figure out
what it was.

912
00:37:35,731 --> 00:37:37,516
We had to fly scientists
down from Sacramento

913
00:37:37,559 --> 00:37:41,171
to figure out what this
creature that we created was.

914
00:37:41,215 --> 00:37:42,521
And they didn't know.

915
00:37:42,564 --> 00:37:44,392
They just said,
we have to just kill it

916
00:37:44,436 --> 00:37:46,307
because we can't let it get
out of the swimming pool.

917
00:37:46,351 --> 00:37:48,962
I mean, it was
almost a better story

918
00:37:49,005 --> 00:37:50,746
than the movie we were making.

919
00:37:50,790 --> 00:37:54,097
- They brought "Piranha"
up to a level

920
00:37:54,141 --> 00:37:56,578
where we did rather well.

921
00:37:56,622 --> 00:38:01,496
We still couldn't and never
will compete with "Jaws,"

922
00:38:01,540 --> 00:38:03,716
but we got up a little bit.

923
00:38:03,759 --> 00:38:07,328
- And that basically
led to me--

924
00:38:07,372 --> 00:38:08,808
as Roger often said,
you know, if you make

925
00:38:08,851 --> 00:38:10,026
two good pictures for me,

926
00:38:10,070 --> 00:38:11,898
you'll never have to work
for me again.

927
00:38:11,941 --> 00:38:16,294
And it led to me being offered
other aquatic adventures,

928
00:38:16,337 --> 00:38:20,602
such as "Orca 2," "Barracuda."

929
00:38:20,646 --> 00:38:23,605
I can't even remember all these
aquatic movies that came out

930
00:38:23,649 --> 00:38:25,259
in the wake of "Jaws,"
because there was

931
00:38:25,303 --> 00:38:28,610
a tremendous need to imitate
the big blockbuster.

932
00:38:28,654 --> 00:38:31,961
- "Alligator" is definitely
part of the sharksploitation

933
00:38:32,005 --> 00:38:35,269
subgenre as well, because it's
straight up like them saying,

934
00:38:35,313 --> 00:38:37,489
well what else is in the water
that can chase people?

935
00:38:37,532 --> 00:38:39,795
Well, alligators.

936
00:38:39,839 --> 00:38:43,712
Basically any time you had
a resort owner, politician,

937
00:38:43,756 --> 00:38:46,367
mayor claiming he could
not close down the beaches

938
00:38:46,411 --> 00:38:47,760
because it's spring break,

939
00:38:47,803 --> 00:38:49,718
4th of July, Labor Day weekend,

940
00:38:49,762 --> 00:38:51,546
it's a "Jaws" rip-off.

941
00:38:51,590 --> 00:38:54,680
The idea of having the moment
where we're all gonna stop

942
00:38:54,723 --> 00:38:57,291
and talk to a scientist
about all sharks do

943
00:38:57,335 --> 00:38:59,380
is swim and eat
and make baby sharks.

944
00:38:59,424 --> 00:39:00,816
- And make baby sharks.

945
00:39:00,860 --> 00:39:02,862
- Usually they always have
the same setup,

946
00:39:02,905 --> 00:39:04,690
where the shark begins
hunting.

947
00:39:04,733 --> 00:39:06,344
And then somebody
is gonna be like,

948
00:39:06,387 --> 00:39:07,780
"There's nothing out there."

949
00:39:07,823 --> 00:39:09,303
And then one person
will be like,

950
00:39:09,347 --> 00:39:11,000
"Oh, no, there's totally
something out there,"

951
00:39:11,044 --> 00:39:13,655
until there's a whole bunch
of deaths.

952
00:39:13,699 --> 00:39:16,397
And then suddenly everyone
has to pay attention to it.

953
00:39:16,441 --> 00:39:17,529
- You have to close the beach.

954
00:39:17,572 --> 00:39:19,357
- And then one
very heroic male

955
00:39:19,400 --> 00:39:20,923
is gonna go kill the shark.

956
00:39:20,967 --> 00:39:22,447
♪

957
00:39:25,319 --> 00:39:27,234
- "Great White"
or "The Last Shark,"

958
00:39:27,277 --> 00:39:29,976
it was one of the most
notorious rip-offs of "Jaws."

959
00:39:30,019 --> 00:39:31,978
- If some of these
sharksploitation films

960
00:39:32,021 --> 00:39:34,676
had kind of been winking
and nodding at "Jaws,"

961
00:39:34,720 --> 00:39:36,852
this one gives it,
like, an outright hug.

962
00:39:36,896 --> 00:39:38,985
- The issue of "Variety"
had a three-page spread

963
00:39:39,028 --> 00:39:40,421
for "Great White."

964
00:39:40,465 --> 00:39:42,205
And they had the poster
and I'm like, well,

965
00:39:42,249 --> 00:39:43,816
obviously
this is a "Jaws" rip-off.

966
00:39:43,859 --> 00:39:44,991
And it's from Italy.

967
00:39:45,034 --> 00:39:46,340
And even then,
I knew Italy was like

968
00:39:46,384 --> 00:39:48,211
the province of movie rip-offs.

969
00:39:48,255 --> 00:39:52,477
- Italians were really ripping
off anything back then--

970
00:39:52,520 --> 00:39:57,264
"Mad Max," "The Exorcist,"
"Rambo," "Dawn of the Dead,"

971
00:39:57,307 --> 00:39:59,745
and, of course, "Jaws."

972
00:39:59,788 --> 00:40:02,922
- Universal decided
that "Great White"

973
00:40:02,965 --> 00:40:08,275
was a copy of "Jaws"
and "Jaws 2."

974
00:40:08,318 --> 00:40:10,233
So there were
so many similarities

975
00:40:10,277 --> 00:40:12,366
that they felt they had
a pretty good case,

976
00:40:12,410 --> 00:40:15,238
so they took legal action.

977
00:40:15,282 --> 00:40:17,458
And we got cease and desist.

978
00:40:17,502 --> 00:40:19,591
And we couldn't do anything
with it anymore.

979
00:40:19,634 --> 00:40:23,508
And they--I think they
even confiscated the prints.

980
00:40:23,551 --> 00:40:26,162
So we were dead in the water.

981
00:40:26,206 --> 00:40:27,686
- And I read about that
and I'm like,

982
00:40:27,729 --> 00:40:29,427
now I'm never gonna get
to see this thing.

983
00:40:29,470 --> 00:40:31,254
And little did I know,
I wouldn't even

984
00:40:31,298 --> 00:40:34,127
get to see it on video
for years and years and years.

985
00:40:34,170 --> 00:40:35,998
And then
I finally got to see it.

986
00:40:36,042 --> 00:40:38,871
And I was like, yeah,
they have a case.

987
00:40:38,914 --> 00:40:41,874
This movie is just
ridiculously derivative.

988
00:40:41,917 --> 00:40:43,919
It's like,
how do they even get away

989
00:40:43,963 --> 00:40:45,443
with this in the first place?

990
00:40:45,486 --> 00:40:47,619
You have James Franciscus
as Peter Benton.

991
00:40:47,662 --> 00:40:50,491
And Vic Morrow is a guy,
like, trying

992
00:40:50,535 --> 00:40:51,971
to do a Robert Shaw accent.

993
00:40:52,014 --> 00:40:54,321
I'm not sure what it is
he's doing there.

994
00:40:54,364 --> 00:40:59,500
- Especially once he's had
his taste of human flesh.

995
00:40:59,544 --> 00:41:01,284
- And just scene after scene
ripped off

996
00:41:01,328 --> 00:41:03,286
from both "Jaws" and "Jaws 2."

997
00:41:03,330 --> 00:41:06,028
They went at it from
every conceivable angle.

998
00:41:10,163 --> 00:41:12,252
- Bruno Mattei was just like,
"You know what?"

999
00:41:12,295 --> 00:41:14,428
Let's just do this
with "Cruel Jaws."

1000
00:41:14,472 --> 00:41:18,214
And he just blatantly rips
entire scenes,

1001
00:41:18,258 --> 00:41:19,520
no fucks given.

1002
00:41:19,564 --> 00:41:22,523
- "Cruel Jaws" steals footage

1003
00:41:22,567 --> 00:41:25,221
from "Jaws 1," "Jaws 2,"

1004
00:41:25,265 --> 00:41:28,224
"Jaws 3-D,"
and "The Last Shark."

1005
00:41:28,268 --> 00:41:29,487
♪

1006
00:41:29,530 --> 00:41:31,619
And then we have "Aatank."

1007
00:41:31,663 --> 00:41:35,797
"Aatank" is the Bollywood
version of "Jaws."

1008
00:41:35,841 --> 00:41:40,149
Actors are singing nearly
all the time in the film,

1009
00:41:40,193 --> 00:41:43,022
even while they are being
eaten by the shark.

1010
00:41:43,065 --> 00:41:46,416
When the shark
finally does appear,

1011
00:41:46,460 --> 00:41:49,463
we only get to see its jaws--

1012
00:41:49,507 --> 00:41:52,205
its gigantic "Jaws."

1013
00:41:52,248 --> 00:41:55,425
And they are definitely not
coming from a real shark.

1014
00:41:55,469 --> 00:41:56,470
♪

1015
00:42:00,082 --> 00:42:02,824
- If you've seen the movie
"Back to the Future Part II,"

1016
00:42:02,868 --> 00:42:04,565
you see a scene in the future.

1017
00:42:04,609 --> 00:42:07,263
We see the main character,
played by Michael J. Fox.

1018
00:42:07,307 --> 00:42:11,180
He's standing outside a cinema
and you see an advertisement

1019
00:42:11,224 --> 00:42:13,748
for "Jaws" Part 19.

1020
00:42:13,792 --> 00:42:15,707
I even think it's called,

1021
00:42:15,750 --> 00:42:18,013
"This time it's really
personal," I think.

1022
00:42:18,057 --> 00:42:20,102
It also has a stupid tagline.

1023
00:42:20,146 --> 00:42:21,887
- So many people
have done sequels

1024
00:42:21,930 --> 00:42:23,366
to all types of movies.

1025
00:42:23,410 --> 00:42:26,152
But you want to make sure
the audience knows

1026
00:42:26,195 --> 00:42:27,545
that a sequel is gonna be
something different,

1027
00:42:27,588 --> 00:42:28,763
something more.

1028
00:42:28,807 --> 00:42:30,983
The sequel's gotta just
step it up a bit.

1029
00:42:31,026 --> 00:42:32,767
Or else, why watch
more of the same?

1030
00:42:32,811 --> 00:42:36,902
And sometimes it's the title
that signals to the viewer,

1031
00:42:36,945 --> 00:42:39,905
this is gonna be different--
more, bigger, better.

1032
00:42:39,948 --> 00:42:42,603
- "Jaws 2" comes out
and tries to make it

1033
00:42:42,647 --> 00:42:45,127
a little bit different,
but not much.

1034
00:42:45,171 --> 00:42:46,520
Somewhere along the lines,
it feels like

1035
00:42:46,564 --> 00:42:49,436
they got the studio note
of, well, it's a sequel,

1036
00:42:49,479 --> 00:42:51,177
so we need more shark.

1037
00:42:51,220 --> 00:42:54,354
And it's not as effective
as you would want it

1038
00:42:54,397 --> 00:42:56,486
to be in a lot of the shots.

1039
00:42:56,530 --> 00:42:59,620
- We didn't have the luxury,
in the second film,

1040
00:42:59,664 --> 00:43:01,143
of hiding the shark.

1041
00:43:01,187 --> 00:43:03,537
Everybody knew
what the shark looked like.

1042
00:43:03,581 --> 00:43:06,279
But we wanted him to be
a fearsome creature.

1043
00:43:06,322 --> 00:43:09,151
And in the opening sequence
where we see

1044
00:43:09,195 --> 00:43:10,413
the shark for the first time,

1045
00:43:10,457 --> 00:43:12,198
where he's chasing
the water skier

1046
00:43:12,241 --> 00:43:15,331
and the panicky boater throws
a can of gasoline,

1047
00:43:15,375 --> 00:43:17,507
it explodes, and the shark's
face is burned,

1048
00:43:17,551 --> 00:43:22,208
that was kind of
a calculated move to say,

1049
00:43:22,251 --> 00:43:23,905
yes, you think you've
seen the shark.

1050
00:43:23,949 --> 00:43:28,344
But this is not just the shark,
it's like Scarface shark.

1051
00:43:28,388 --> 00:43:31,086
You know,
this time he's really angry.

1052
00:43:31,130 --> 00:43:32,653
- That, of course, sparked,
you know,

1053
00:43:32,697 --> 00:43:33,959
"just when you thought
it was safe to go

1054
00:43:34,002 --> 00:43:36,091
back in the water,"
which is probably

1055
00:43:36,135 --> 00:43:37,527
the most famous tagline.

1056
00:43:37,571 --> 00:43:39,660
And it's been, you know,
parodied

1057
00:43:39,704 --> 00:43:43,185
and spun off on ever since.

1058
00:43:43,229 --> 00:43:45,013
But it's just become
so associated

1059
00:43:45,057 --> 00:43:46,449
with the whole franchise.

1060
00:43:46,493 --> 00:43:48,277
And it may be one
of the things people

1061
00:43:48,321 --> 00:43:49,801
most remember about that film.

1062
00:43:49,844 --> 00:43:51,759
- The second "Jaws" movie
had come out right

1063
00:43:51,803 --> 00:43:53,065
around the time of "Piranha."

1064
00:43:53,108 --> 00:43:54,719
And for whatever reason,
Universal

1065
00:43:54,762 --> 00:43:56,982
was very concerned and annoyed
that Roger was putting out

1066
00:43:57,025 --> 00:43:59,898
his rip-off of "Jaws"
the same year

1067
00:43:59,941 --> 00:44:01,464
that "Jaws 2" was coming out.

1068
00:44:01,508 --> 00:44:04,250
And so they apparently
threatened an injunction.

1069
00:44:04,293 --> 00:44:08,950
And I discovered much later
that Spielberg had stepped in

1070
00:44:08,994 --> 00:44:11,692
to Universal and apparently
had seen "Piranha"

1071
00:44:11,736 --> 00:44:12,911
and said, no, you don't get it.

1072
00:44:12,954 --> 00:44:14,564
This is a spoof.

1073
00:44:14,608 --> 00:44:17,306
This isn't really a rip-off,
although it is a rip-off.

1074
00:44:17,350 --> 00:44:23,312
And we basically got away with
it, I guess is the phrase.

1075
00:44:23,356 --> 00:44:27,316
And because of that, I was
offered "Jaws 3, People 0,"

1076
00:44:27,360 --> 00:44:29,579
which was
a combination production

1077
00:44:29,623 --> 00:44:32,495
between The National Lampoon
and Universal Pictures.

1078
00:44:35,194 --> 00:44:37,239
- I was over at Universal.

1079
00:44:37,283 --> 00:44:39,677
My next-door neighbors
were Zanuck and Brown,

1080
00:44:39,720 --> 00:44:41,026
Dick Zanuck and David Brown.

1081
00:44:41,069 --> 00:44:42,897
And he, first thing he said
to me, is Dick and I

1082
00:44:42,941 --> 00:44:45,813
would love to make
a movie with you guys.

1083
00:44:45,857 --> 00:44:48,947
So out of the blue, I just
started kidding around.

1084
00:44:48,990 --> 00:44:53,429
And I said,
"Jaws 3, People Nothing."

1085
00:44:53,473 --> 00:44:55,214
I said,
Peter Benchley walks out

1086
00:44:55,257 --> 00:44:57,564
of his house
in a bathing suit,

1087
00:44:57,607 --> 00:44:59,871
jumps into his pool,
and disappears.

1088
00:44:59,914 --> 00:45:01,568
And the next thing,
we see a fin

1089
00:45:01,611 --> 00:45:03,570
floating around in the pool.

1090
00:45:03,613 --> 00:45:05,354
I said, I know it's ridiculous.

1091
00:45:05,398 --> 00:45:06,834
He's, "No, no, go on."

1092
00:45:06,878 --> 00:45:10,272
So I had no idea
where I was going, but I went.

1093
00:45:10,316 --> 00:45:12,274
And he said,
"I love it. I love it.

1094
00:45:12,318 --> 00:45:14,755
I'll call you tomorrow.
We're gonna make this movie."

1095
00:45:14,799 --> 00:45:17,976
As soon as I got the call
from David Brown telling me

1096
00:45:18,019 --> 00:45:20,674
that the studio is doing
the movie, I left my office

1097
00:45:20,718 --> 00:45:22,545
and I walked into
the editorial office.

1098
00:45:22,589 --> 00:45:23,895
I knew who I was looking for.

1099
00:45:23,938 --> 00:45:25,723
And I walked over
to the two of them.

1100
00:45:25,766 --> 00:45:28,813
I said, Tod, you,
and I turned to the other,

1101
00:45:28,856 --> 00:45:31,076
the first--the guy
I was really looking for,

1102
00:45:31,119 --> 00:45:32,599
John Hughes.

1103
00:45:32,642 --> 00:45:34,906
I said, John, you and Tod
are writing this script.

1104
00:45:34,949 --> 00:45:36,995
And I handed him
the short story.

1105
00:45:37,038 --> 00:45:41,216
And then I hired Joe Dante
to direct the picture.

1106
00:45:41,260 --> 00:45:43,741
- The National Lampoon people
wanted to make an R-rated

1107
00:45:43,784 --> 00:45:45,786
comedy like "Animal House."

1108
00:45:45,830 --> 00:45:50,008
And the more conservative
Zanuck and Brown team

1109
00:45:50,051 --> 00:45:53,359
wanted to make it PG
and have it be a wide release,

1110
00:45:53,402 --> 00:45:54,621
family picture.

1111
00:45:54,664 --> 00:45:56,928
- First of all,
Bo Derek was nude

1112
00:45:56,971 --> 00:45:59,887
from the waist up
through much of--

1113
00:45:59,931 --> 00:46:01,541
a good deal of the picture.

1114
00:46:01,584 --> 00:46:04,109
And secondly, that's what
we made, was R-rated movies.

1115
00:46:04,152 --> 00:46:07,852
The National Lampoon
did not make PG movies.

1116
00:46:07,895 --> 00:46:10,724
- I guess
wiser heads prevailed.

1117
00:46:10,768 --> 00:46:12,987
And I think it was, you know,
Sid Sheinberg

1118
00:46:13,031 --> 00:46:17,383
and maybe Lew Wasserman
and certainly Spielberg.

1119
00:46:17,426 --> 00:46:20,125
They said, why do you
want to take, you know,

1120
00:46:20,168 --> 00:46:23,737
a great franchise and mock it?

1121
00:46:23,781 --> 00:46:26,479
- I think the project died
because they just

1122
00:46:26,522 --> 00:46:28,046
couldn't agree on what movie
they were making.

1123
00:46:28,089 --> 00:46:30,831
And you can't go into a movie
with two entities

1124
00:46:30,875 --> 00:46:32,790
as powerful as The Lampoon was
at that time

1125
00:46:32,833 --> 00:46:33,921
and Zanuck and Brown

1126
00:46:33,965 --> 00:46:35,531
and have them fighting
constantly

1127
00:46:35,575 --> 00:46:36,881
through the entire movie.

1128
00:46:36,924 --> 00:46:39,753
It's just a bad idea.

1129
00:46:39,797 --> 00:46:42,060
And I think
they just pulled the plug.

1130
00:46:42,103 --> 00:46:43,975
- So they had to choose
between me and Spielberg.

1131
00:46:44,018 --> 00:46:45,977
And I suspect
they made the right choice.

1132
00:46:48,066 --> 00:46:50,590
- They were gonna do
"Jaws 3, People 0."

1133
00:46:50,633 --> 00:46:53,375
So Verna said,
"Go talk to Landsburg."

1134
00:46:53,419 --> 00:46:54,550
They came back.

1135
00:46:54,594 --> 00:46:56,204
I got the directing job.

1136
00:46:56,248 --> 00:47:00,034
And they got all excited about
doing this 3D "Jaws" movie.

1137
00:47:00,078 --> 00:47:03,646
And so that was it.

1138
00:47:03,690 --> 00:47:06,214
Then, that's--
my problem started.

1139
00:47:06,258 --> 00:47:09,478
- Because it was 3D,
there was an awful--

1140
00:47:09,522 --> 00:47:13,874
an awful lot of complicated
technical requirements

1141
00:47:13,918 --> 00:47:15,267
for the filming.

1142
00:47:15,310 --> 00:47:17,399
There wasn't much I could do

1143
00:47:17,443 --> 00:47:19,314
to write new props
or new scenery

1144
00:47:19,358 --> 00:47:20,838
or new action,
because it had all

1145
00:47:20,881 --> 00:47:23,928
been storyboarded
very carefully for 3D,

1146
00:47:23,971 --> 00:47:26,234
which has its own requirements.

1147
00:47:26,278 --> 00:47:29,020
- Let me tell you something
about 3D.

1148
00:47:29,063 --> 00:47:30,673
Here's our screen proportion.

1149
00:47:30,717 --> 00:47:32,371
We're taking 35 millimeter.

1150
00:47:32,414 --> 00:47:34,199
So this is your
screen proportion.

1151
00:47:34,242 --> 00:47:38,029
Now, if it was a snake,
you could slide that out

1152
00:47:38,072 --> 00:47:40,553
right out into the audience.

1153
00:47:40,596 --> 00:47:42,685
But they have a thing
called the dorsal fin.

1154
00:47:42,729 --> 00:47:45,775
And as soon as the dorsal fin
hits the pickup,

1155
00:47:45,819 --> 00:47:47,255
it stops.

1156
00:47:47,299 --> 00:47:50,955
So that damn dorsal fin
kills you on 3D.

1157
00:47:50,998 --> 00:47:52,957
I could get the head out
a little bit,

1158
00:47:53,000 --> 00:47:55,089
but I couldn't get it
into the audience.

1159
00:47:55,133 --> 00:47:56,917
Oh, I had kids.

1160
00:47:56,961 --> 00:47:58,701
There were things in the park.

1161
00:47:58,745 --> 00:48:01,748
I had an octopus thing goes
out and other things go out.

1162
00:48:01,791 --> 00:48:05,099
And of course, the studio,
they just throw stuff out.

1163
00:48:05,143 --> 00:48:06,405
Wasn't my concept.

1164
00:48:06,448 --> 00:48:09,060
My concept for 3D
was the depth.

1165
00:48:09,103 --> 00:48:11,932
But no, no, no,
you gotta throw stuff out.

1166
00:48:11,976 --> 00:48:13,934
- I remember
from the beginning, like,

1167
00:48:13,978 --> 00:48:15,588
you expect it's a 3D "Jaws,"

1168
00:48:15,631 --> 00:48:17,329
they're gonna open
with something really great.

1169
00:48:17,372 --> 00:48:19,113
And the first big 3D effect

1170
00:48:19,157 --> 00:48:22,638
is a fish head floating
into your face.

1171
00:48:22,682 --> 00:48:24,466
- For me, "Jaws 3" is where

1172
00:48:24,510 --> 00:48:26,468
"Jaws" becomes
an exploitation movie.

1173
00:48:26,512 --> 00:48:28,688
It's where "Jaws" literally
jumps the shark.

1174
00:48:28,731 --> 00:48:32,039
Because it really is trying
to do something different

1175
00:48:32,083 --> 00:48:34,346
to set itself apart
from itself.

1176
00:48:34,389 --> 00:48:36,652
- I saw "Jaws 3" too late.

1177
00:48:36,696 --> 00:48:39,612
Like I was--you know,
"Independence Day"

1178
00:48:39,655 --> 00:48:42,180
had been made and all
these great VFX movies.

1179
00:48:42,223 --> 00:48:44,704
And I think I just saw through
all of, like,

1180
00:48:44,747 --> 00:48:49,187
the weird shark floating
towards the glass,

1181
00:48:49,230 --> 00:48:50,884
like, then the glass, like,

1182
00:48:50,928 --> 00:48:53,452
mysteriously breaks
towards the screen.

1183
00:48:53,495 --> 00:48:55,541
And I mean, fuck,
it's good, actually,

1184
00:48:55,584 --> 00:48:56,846
the more you think about it.

1185
00:48:56,890 --> 00:48:59,153
- The shark is moving
with the speed

1186
00:48:59,197 --> 00:49:02,200
and ferocity
of the Goodyear blimp.

1187
00:49:02,243 --> 00:49:03,679
And it's the climax
of the movie.

1188
00:49:03,723 --> 00:49:05,812
It's supposed to go
bang, crash,

1189
00:49:05,855 --> 00:49:08,684
boom, collapse, broken glass,

1190
00:49:08,728 --> 00:49:10,686
water flooding in, everything.

1191
00:49:10,730 --> 00:49:13,124
But the shark's approach
just takes forever.

1192
00:49:13,167 --> 00:49:15,039
You go, "One, one thousand,
two, one thousand..."

1193
00:49:15,082 --> 00:49:16,518
He's gonna hit the screen
any minute.

1194
00:49:16,562 --> 00:49:19,565
And it's 3D, so he's--he's--

1195
00:49:19,608 --> 00:49:22,133
the shark is coming
at the screen.

1196
00:49:22,176 --> 00:49:26,311
So the climactic shot
of the movie is dog shit.

1197
00:49:26,354 --> 00:49:30,358
- When people talk to me about
1, 2, or 3 for various scenes.

1198
00:49:30,402 --> 00:49:32,491
But nobody ever mentions 4.

1199
00:49:32,534 --> 00:49:34,362
- I mean, the problem
with "Jaws, The Revenge"

1200
00:49:34,406 --> 00:49:36,234
was it was a joke
before it even opened.

1201
00:49:36,277 --> 00:49:38,540
Because that tagline,
"This time it's personal,"

1202
00:49:38,584 --> 00:49:40,673
I don't know
who came up with that one.

1203
00:49:40,716 --> 00:49:43,067
But again, it made the film
kind of a punchline

1204
00:49:43,110 --> 00:49:44,372
before it even opened.

1205
00:49:44,416 --> 00:49:47,462
- "Jaws, The Revenge"
comes out in 1987.

1206
00:49:47,506 --> 00:49:50,813
And though I'm sure adults
and critics at the time

1207
00:49:50,857 --> 00:49:55,427
fucking hated that movie,
I loved "Jaws, The Revenge."

1208
00:49:55,470 --> 00:49:57,168
Like, it knows
what it's doing.

1209
00:49:57,211 --> 00:50:00,171
It is the shark
that has telepathically

1210
00:50:00,214 --> 00:50:02,564
chased the family.

1211
00:50:02,608 --> 00:50:04,175
So it functions
as a straight-up slasher,

1212
00:50:04,218 --> 00:50:06,090
because it is
specifically targeting

1213
00:50:06,133 --> 00:50:08,614
members of this family
and trying

1214
00:50:08,657 --> 00:50:11,051
to find ways to get them.

1215
00:50:11,095 --> 00:50:13,401
Now, at that point,
logic might say,

1216
00:50:13,445 --> 00:50:14,837
like, well,
just don't go in the water.

1217
00:50:14,881 --> 00:50:17,231
Like, if Jason can only
kill you in the water,

1218
00:50:17,275 --> 00:50:18,319
you just don't go in the water.

1219
00:50:18,363 --> 00:50:19,755
- And I remember
at a certain point

1220
00:50:19,799 --> 00:50:20,974
I was reading the script.

1221
00:50:21,018 --> 00:50:23,977
And there was a part
where Lorraine Gary

1222
00:50:24,021 --> 00:50:25,413
realizes that it's personal,

1223
00:50:25,457 --> 00:50:27,676
the shark is coming after
her children.

1224
00:50:27,720 --> 00:50:30,505
And she's so infuriated
that she gets in the ship

1225
00:50:30,549 --> 00:50:32,377
and she goes out
after the shark.

1226
00:50:34,118 --> 00:50:36,685
Now, I said,
that's some white people stuff.

1227
00:50:36,729 --> 00:50:40,080
Now, I said, what is the plan?

1228
00:50:40,124 --> 00:50:42,256
Now, we've seen
this big-ass shark

1229
00:50:42,300 --> 00:50:43,910
the size of a school bus,

1230
00:50:43,953 --> 00:50:46,043
you know, kill up
a whole lot of people.

1231
00:50:46,086 --> 00:50:48,219
Why is she going in this...
[laughing]

1232
00:50:48,262 --> 00:50:49,307
What is she doing?

1233
00:50:49,350 --> 00:50:50,482
What's the plan?
