01:00:09,170 --> 01:00:11,172
the schedule 52 weeks
a year every Saturday night.

1481
01:00:11,216 --> 01:00:12,696
I would love to have
one of these,

1482
01:00:12,739 --> 01:00:14,349
but there's just not
enough good ones to buy

1483
01:00:14,393 --> 01:00:15,742
and not enough available.

1484
01:00:15,786 --> 01:00:18,397
So I said,
"Well, if we can't buy them,

1485
01:00:18,440 --> 01:00:19,703
maybe we should make them."

1486
01:00:19,746 --> 01:00:22,662
We started with one
as an experiment.

1487
01:00:22,706 --> 01:00:24,142
And it worked.

1488
01:00:24,185 --> 01:00:25,534
So after that, we said,
"Oh, let's try a few more."

1489
01:00:25,578 --> 01:00:26,840
Management liked the ratings.

1490
01:00:26,884 --> 01:00:27,972
They liked what we were doing.

1491
01:00:28,015 --> 01:00:29,277
"Oh, try another four."

1492
01:00:29,321 --> 01:00:30,757
And after that,
"Try a few more."

1493
01:00:30,801 --> 01:00:33,194
All of a sudden, we were doing
24 movies a year.

1494
01:00:33,238 --> 01:00:35,240
A few years later, we were
actually doing 36 a year.

1495
01:00:35,283 --> 01:00:37,155
We were doing three a month,
which was incredible.

1496
01:00:37,198 --> 01:00:38,765
It was crazy.

1497
01:00:38,809 --> 01:00:40,114
When we first started
doing these movies,

1498
01:00:40,158 --> 01:00:41,899
we didn't go for the big,
over-the-top titles.

1499
01:00:41,942 --> 01:00:44,336
But then we slowly started
getting into titles

1500
01:00:44,379 --> 01:00:45,729
that were a little bit
more over the top.

1501
01:00:45,772 --> 01:00:47,861
And you know, we have
these titles

1502
01:00:47,905 --> 01:00:49,863
that grabbed people's
attention.

1503
01:00:49,907 --> 01:00:52,126
And then the press started
talking about these movies.

1504
01:00:52,170 --> 01:00:53,911
And then the audience realized,

1505
01:00:53,954 --> 01:00:55,956
"Oh, these guys are having
a blast.

1506
01:00:56,000 --> 01:00:58,611
These guys are
just having fun."

1507
01:00:58,655 --> 01:01:01,788
- These movies are
made off titles.

1508
01:01:01,832 --> 01:01:03,660
The network just, like, looks
at the movies,

1509
01:01:03,703 --> 01:01:06,314
and they're like,
"Okay, we like Sharkacaine

1510
01:01:06,358 --> 01:01:09,143
and we like Mega Shark."

1511
01:01:09,187 --> 01:01:12,930
And let's see
some rough outlines.

1512
01:01:12,973 --> 01:01:14,235
And then it's
like a paragraph.

1513
01:01:14,279 --> 01:01:15,889
And they read it.
They're like, "Mm,

1514
01:01:15,933 --> 01:01:18,109
let's do sort of something
like this instead."

1515
01:01:18,152 --> 01:01:19,719
And then they, like, see
a treatment.

1516
01:01:19,763 --> 01:01:22,374
And then they're like,
"We like the treatment,

1517
01:01:22,417 --> 01:01:24,158
but how about instead of this,
we do this?"

1518
01:01:24,202 --> 01:01:25,986
- I've done pictures
for them before, yeah.

1519
01:01:26,030 --> 01:01:28,119
And their process
is basically, you know,

1520
01:01:28,162 --> 01:01:30,425
"Bring us ten ideas and just
throw them around."

1521
01:01:30,469 --> 01:01:32,297
And they may do none
of the ten,

1522
01:01:32,340 --> 01:01:34,865
but they may do, like,
the space aliens

1523
01:01:34,908 --> 01:01:35,996
from the first movie you did

1524
01:01:36,040 --> 01:01:37,998
and then this giant crustacean

1525
01:01:38,042 --> 01:01:39,565
from the second movie
you had an idea.

1526
01:01:39,608 --> 01:01:40,914
And we'll put those together

1527
01:01:40,958 --> 01:01:42,916
so it's giant crustaceans
from space.

1528
01:01:42,960 --> 01:01:44,570
- And then they
approve the script.

1529
01:01:44,613 --> 01:01:46,485
So it's
this really backwards process

1530
01:01:46,528 --> 01:01:47,921
from what filmmaking
normally is,

1531
01:01:47,965 --> 01:01:49,314
where there's, like, a script,

1532
01:01:49,357 --> 01:01:51,185
and you have this script,
and that's the story,

1533
01:01:51,229 --> 01:01:52,709
and then you get that,
like, financed,

1534
01:01:52,752 --> 01:01:54,841
and it goes through
all the, you know, rigmarole

1535
01:01:54,885 --> 01:01:56,190
that a movie normally does.

1536
01:01:56,234 --> 01:01:58,236
These are literally
just a name.

1537
01:01:58,279 --> 01:02:01,718
[laughs] And that's the--
that's the selling point.

1538
01:02:01,761 --> 01:02:04,895
Like that's the--that's what
the movie is at its core.

1539
01:02:04,938 --> 01:02:07,245
- And when you mix genres,
you actually come up

1540
01:02:07,288 --> 01:02:08,899
with movies that really work.

1541
01:02:08,942 --> 01:02:11,031
You don't have to stick
to the exact same genre.

1542
01:02:11,075 --> 01:02:12,729
You want to take something
people love, sharks,

1543
01:02:12,772 --> 01:02:14,078
and then expand it.

1544
01:02:14,121 --> 01:02:17,037
- And the Asylum really rode
that whole trend.

1545
01:02:17,081 --> 01:02:18,822
- We started off
in arthouse movies.

1546
01:02:18,865 --> 01:02:20,998
And then from there,
we did horror films.

1547
01:02:21,041 --> 01:02:23,174
We were known for--
as a B-horror film,

1548
01:02:23,217 --> 01:02:24,784
you know, slasher movie place.

1549
01:02:24,828 --> 01:02:26,743
And then we were known
to a big segment

1550
01:02:26,786 --> 01:02:29,397
as mockbusters.

1551
01:02:29,441 --> 01:02:32,400
- We've sort of got
a reputation for making

1552
01:02:32,444 --> 01:02:36,013
what the "New York Post"
dubbed mockbusters,

1553
01:02:36,056 --> 01:02:40,757
where we make movies that are
similar in theme and concept

1554
01:02:40,800 --> 01:02:42,715
to big studio releases.

1555
01:02:42,759 --> 01:02:44,195
- It's our own genre.

1556
01:02:44,238 --> 01:02:49,591
We took over that,
you know, monocle, and we--

1557
01:02:49,635 --> 01:02:51,245
it's something
that we embraced.

1558
01:02:51,289 --> 01:02:53,595
And we've been
enjoying it ever since.

1559
01:02:53,639 --> 01:02:56,468
We were a young company
that had its own genre.

1560
01:02:56,511 --> 01:02:59,645
- Mtv.com--I don't know if
they're still around anymore,

1561
01:02:59,688 --> 01:03:01,429
but they had contacted me
and said,

1562
01:03:01,473 --> 01:03:04,519
"Hey, can you give us
an exclusive on a trailer?"

1563
01:03:04,563 --> 01:03:05,738
And we said yes.

1564
01:03:05,782 --> 01:03:07,914
And it went crazy:

1565
01:03:07,958 --> 01:03:10,308
millions, millions of hits.

1566
01:03:10,351 --> 01:03:14,094
And that was our first taste
of a viral success

1567
01:03:14,138 --> 01:03:16,662
of one of the films.

1568
01:03:16,705 --> 01:03:20,100
We were just trying
to make a Godzilla.

1569
01:03:20,144 --> 01:03:22,494
You know, it was
giant creatures.

1570
01:03:22,537 --> 01:03:24,801
And that was one of the things
that the Japanese,

1571
01:03:24,844 --> 01:03:28,892
not surprisingly, you know,
really insisted upon.

1572
01:03:28,935 --> 01:03:30,415
It's gotta be giant.

1573
01:03:30,458 --> 01:03:34,027
And you know, you really have
to be creative in terms

1574
01:03:34,071 --> 01:03:36,900
of, you know, what are you
gonna do with a giant shark?

1575
01:03:36,943 --> 01:03:40,686
Well, of course, you're gonna
take down a jetliner.

1576
01:03:40,729 --> 01:03:41,818
- Holy shit.

1577
01:03:41,861 --> 01:03:43,210
[dramatic music]

1578
01:03:44,908 --> 01:03:46,039
[woman screaming]

1579
01:03:46,083 --> 01:03:47,693
- The fact that a shark
would jump

1580
01:03:47,736 --> 01:03:50,261
all the way up
and take out a jet,

1581
01:03:50,304 --> 01:03:51,784
to me, just was ridiculous.

1582
01:03:51,828 --> 01:03:54,656
And I fought to not even
have that shot in the movie

1583
01:03:54,700 --> 01:03:55,701
and not even do it.

1584
01:03:55,744 --> 01:03:57,094
And it turned out
to be, I guess,

1585
01:03:57,137 --> 01:04:00,184
one of the most iconic parts
of "Mega Shark."

1586
01:04:00,227 --> 01:04:01,881
- That launched
some more orders

1587
01:04:01,925 --> 01:04:04,188
for more shark
or shark hybrid movies.

1588
01:04:04,231 --> 01:04:07,017
- And you see
a lot of integration.

1589
01:04:07,060 --> 01:04:09,541
It's not a shark movie anymore.

1590
01:04:09,584 --> 01:04:13,110
You take the shark as an animal
and then take something else.

1591
01:04:13,153 --> 01:04:16,678
And then you combine it to
make an even more crazy movie.

1592
01:04:16,722 --> 01:04:18,419
Some of the most
well-known is where

1593
01:04:18,463 --> 01:04:22,119
you take, of course, a shark
and combine it with a man.

1594
01:04:22,162 --> 01:04:23,772
So you have a Sharkman.

1595
01:04:23,816 --> 01:04:28,386
But you also see
when you combine two animals.

1596
01:04:28,429 --> 01:04:32,129
The most well-known is perhaps
the movie called "Sharktopus."

1597
01:04:32,172 --> 01:04:34,261
- I said to Roger,
"Roger, I've got a movie

1598
01:04:34,305 --> 01:04:37,264
I want you to make for us
called 'Sharktopus.'"

1599
01:04:37,308 --> 01:04:39,788
And Roger Corman is on
the other end of the line.

1600
01:04:39,832 --> 01:04:40,833
I hear him pause.

1601
01:04:40,877 --> 01:04:42,661
He takes a breath.
And he goes,

1602
01:04:42,704 --> 01:04:45,533
"Tom, I have this theory

1603
01:04:45,577 --> 01:04:48,667
"that you can take
the audience to a point,

1604
01:04:48,710 --> 01:04:50,538
"but you can't take them
beyond that point.

1605
01:04:50,582 --> 01:04:52,497
"You can only take
the audience so far,

1606
01:04:52,540 --> 01:04:55,021
and I think that 'Sharktopus'
goes too far."

1607
01:04:55,065 --> 01:04:56,109
I said, "That's okay, Roger.

1608
01:04:56,153 --> 01:04:57,110
"We'll find
another film with you.

1609
01:04:57,154 --> 01:04:58,372
"I love working with you.

1610
01:04:58,416 --> 01:04:59,591
"I want to work with you
on something else.

1611
01:04:59,634 --> 01:05:00,809
I'll just call the Asylum."

1612
01:05:00,853 --> 01:05:02,768
And I knew by saying that,

1613
01:05:02,811 --> 01:05:05,292
that was gonna kind of get him.

1614
01:05:05,336 --> 01:05:06,946
I hear him take a deep breath
on the other side.

1615
01:05:06,990 --> 01:05:10,254
He's like,
"Well, let's not be too hasty.

1616
01:05:10,297 --> 01:05:13,953
I think I can find a way
to make 'Sharktopus' work."

1617
01:05:13,997 --> 01:05:17,522
- And not only
you're combining two animals,

1618
01:05:17,565 --> 01:05:19,089
you're also taking the shark

1619
01:05:19,132 --> 01:05:22,092
out of its normal environment,
the sea,

1620
01:05:22,135 --> 01:05:24,224
and taking it somewhere else.

1621
01:05:24,268 --> 01:05:26,009
- You could be standing
on a street corner

1622
01:05:26,052 --> 01:05:28,098
and the shark can come out
and get you.

1623
01:05:28,141 --> 01:05:30,970
Because that's--
that's the concept now.

1624
01:05:31,014 --> 01:05:33,494
I mean, the logic is,
there's no logic.

1625
01:05:33,538 --> 01:05:35,105
- We have movies
like "Ghost Shark."

1626
01:05:35,148 --> 01:05:36,976
- That movie was so special.

1627
01:05:37,020 --> 01:05:38,586
That was like a haunted shark

1628
01:05:38,630 --> 01:05:41,981
that would come after you
in bodies of water.

1629
01:05:42,025 --> 01:05:43,417
And then the best part
was that,

1630
01:05:43,461 --> 01:05:44,897
towards the end of the movie,

1631
01:05:44,941 --> 01:05:49,641
the bodies of water got
more and more, like, nuanced.

1632
01:05:49,684 --> 01:05:51,730
[laughing] Like--
like, I think it came out

1633
01:05:51,773 --> 01:05:53,775
of, like, sink water,

1634
01:05:53,819 --> 01:05:55,038
steam from a bath.

1635
01:05:55,081 --> 01:05:56,604
- Or you know, if it's raining,

1636
01:05:56,648 --> 01:05:58,998
God forbid, the shark can swim
through the air.

1637
01:05:59,042 --> 01:06:00,260
There's, like,
a bikini car wash,

1638
01:06:00,304 --> 01:06:01,827
and a girl gets, like,
pulled into a bucket.

1639
01:06:01,870 --> 01:06:03,350
- Drinking water
might be dangerous.

1640
01:06:03,394 --> 01:06:04,438
A pool could be dangerous.

1641
01:06:04,482 --> 01:06:05,874
A Slip 'N Slide
can be dangerous.

1642
01:06:05,918 --> 01:06:08,399
I usually had a rule
in most of the movies

1643
01:06:08,442 --> 01:06:10,967
that, you know,
adults and teens,

1644
01:06:11,010 --> 01:06:13,143
but not kids,
would become victims.

1645
01:06:13,186 --> 01:06:15,710
But in this one,
the director really fought

1646
01:06:15,754 --> 01:06:17,930
for that gag,
which he just felt

1647
01:06:17,974 --> 01:06:19,410
was gonna be a great gag.

1648
01:06:19,453 --> 01:06:21,020
I was like, "Okay, let's try
it and see if it works."

1649
01:06:21,064 --> 01:06:22,195
And people love that scene.

1650
01:06:22,239 --> 01:06:23,544
- So that's quite fun

1651
01:06:23,588 --> 01:06:26,069
to see how they're taking
the shark

1652
01:06:26,112 --> 01:06:27,244
away from
its normal environment

1653
01:06:27,287 --> 01:06:29,420
and then put it
in somewhere else.

1654
01:06:29,463 --> 01:06:31,900
You also have movies
like "Nightmare Shark,"

1655
01:06:31,944 --> 01:06:33,815
where the shark
is quite like

1656
01:06:33,859 --> 01:06:35,121
"Nightmare on Elm Street."

1657
01:06:35,165 --> 01:06:37,428
We take the shark
into people's dreams.

1658
01:06:39,517 --> 01:06:41,998
- For the shark TV movies
for the Syfy Channel,

1659
01:06:42,041 --> 01:06:44,826
there's a very specific
shark formula.

1660
01:06:44,870 --> 01:06:47,438
So they are movies
that play out in eight acts

1661
01:06:47,481 --> 01:06:49,222
with seven commercial breaks.

1662
01:06:49,266 --> 01:06:52,530
And you're required to have,
in each act,

1663
01:06:52,573 --> 01:06:55,054
a major gag and a minor gag.

1664
01:06:55,098 --> 01:06:57,970
So a major gag is one where
you have to show the shark.

1665
01:06:58,014 --> 01:06:59,754
And then a minor gag
would be like, you know,

1666
01:06:59,798 --> 01:07:02,105
a shark POV looking
at someone out of the water

1667
01:07:02,148 --> 01:07:03,280
and then they go, "Aah!"

1668
01:07:03,323 --> 01:07:04,759
And then, like,
blood splashes.

1669
01:07:04,803 --> 01:07:07,066
[laughs]
Just kind of implying it.

1670
01:07:07,110 --> 01:07:08,633
- One of the things
for the shark movies,

1671
01:07:08,676 --> 01:07:09,982
certainly
for the low-budget ones,

1672
01:07:10,026 --> 01:07:12,071
what you try to do
is keep it, you know,

1673
01:07:12,115 --> 01:07:13,464
we're either underwater

1674
01:07:13,507 --> 01:07:14,943
or they're doing
something crazy

1675
01:07:14,987 --> 01:07:16,293
flying through space.

1676
01:07:16,336 --> 01:07:19,557
So we did shark swimming
through the sand.

1677
01:07:19,600 --> 01:07:21,863
It's like,
well, what else can we do?

1678
01:07:21,907 --> 01:07:23,430
The sand shark was brown.

1679
01:07:23,474 --> 01:07:25,171
And if I just negatived
all the textures,

1680
01:07:25,215 --> 01:07:26,520
it became blue and looked icy.

1681
01:07:26,564 --> 01:07:29,045
And we're like...[gasps]
A shark in the snow!

1682
01:07:29,088 --> 01:07:30,307
- The sort of secret to these--

1683
01:07:30,350 --> 01:07:31,960
like, the, like,
climax moments,

1684
01:07:32,004 --> 01:07:33,527
the action moments
that try to show the shark,

1685
01:07:33,571 --> 01:07:35,964
like, in three different ways.

1686
01:07:36,008 --> 01:07:38,358
And so, like,
underwater it jumps out.

1687
01:07:38,402 --> 01:07:39,707
Over water, slow-mo.

1688
01:07:39,751 --> 01:07:41,796
And then, like, right--
looking from

1689
01:07:41,840 --> 01:07:43,363
where you see it, like,
coming right at her.

1690
01:07:43,407 --> 01:07:44,582
And then, like, cut to a wide,

1691
01:07:44,625 --> 01:07:46,497
and it's, like,
this giant, crazy shark.

1692
01:07:46,540 --> 01:07:48,107
And she just shoots it
right in the mouth

1693
01:07:48,151 --> 01:07:49,804
and it flies into the air
and just explodes

1694
01:07:49,848 --> 01:07:51,850
in, like, gore and fireworks.

1695
01:07:51,893 --> 01:07:53,591
And then the whole town claps.

1696
01:07:53,634 --> 01:07:56,115
♪

1697
01:07:56,159 --> 01:07:58,161
- The scene where the shark
comes out of the water--

1698
01:07:58,204 --> 01:07:59,379
that was
in the original script.

1699
01:07:59,423 --> 01:08:00,772
That was always there.

1700
01:08:00,815 --> 01:08:02,643
That was a part, you know,
of the six-headed shark.

1701
01:08:02,687 --> 01:08:03,949
Like, what can we do
with the shark,

1702
01:08:03,992 --> 01:08:05,342
you know, that's different,

1703
01:08:05,385 --> 01:08:07,474
that hasn't been done
in the other shark movies?

1704
01:08:07,518 --> 01:08:09,041
Originally, I wanted it
to walk.

1705
01:08:09,085 --> 01:08:11,261
Like, I did an animation,
almost like fingers.

1706
01:08:11,304 --> 01:08:13,045
And I think they thought
that was too funny.

1707
01:08:13,089 --> 01:08:14,481
You know, it's like a hand.

1708
01:08:14,525 --> 01:08:16,353
And so it's--now it's flat

1709
01:08:16,396 --> 01:08:17,963
and it's kind of,
like, pushing itself.

1710
01:08:18,006 --> 01:08:19,356
It's still hilarious.

1711
01:08:19,399 --> 01:08:20,966
I'm like, what's
the difference, you know?

1712
01:08:21,009 --> 01:08:23,360
- The visual effects
of the sharks came in,

1713
01:08:23,403 --> 01:08:25,362
and they're adorable.

1714
01:08:25,405 --> 01:08:28,234
And they're still in there
as the most adorable things

1715
01:08:28,278 --> 01:08:29,540
you've ever seen.

1716
01:08:29,583 --> 01:08:31,194
I was like, "Okay, well,
it's not gonna be

1717
01:08:31,237 --> 01:08:33,457
the scariest
of all the shark attacks."

1718
01:08:33,500 --> 01:08:36,242
- The way it works is,
we don't pitch our buyers,

1719
