01:27:13,837 --> 01:27:16,056
is really attractive,
not only because it allows us

2204
01:27:16,100 --> 01:27:18,407
to stake our claim
over part of the environment

2205
01:27:18,450 --> 01:27:21,279
we might not understand,
but because it allows us

2206
01:27:21,323 --> 01:27:23,325
to keep that imagination alive.

2207
01:27:23,368 --> 01:27:25,979
- I knew that there was
such a thing as the megalodon.

2208
01:27:26,023 --> 01:27:27,633
I looked it up online.

2209
01:27:27,677 --> 01:27:32,508
And I saw families of people
standing inside these jaws.

2210
01:27:32,551 --> 01:27:35,293
These were huge
fucking real sharks

2211
01:27:35,337 --> 01:27:36,555
from back in the day.

2212
01:27:36,599 --> 01:27:39,602
- What were they saying,
six fully-grown men

2213
01:27:39,645 --> 01:27:41,821
could be swallowed
by the megalodon?

2214
01:27:41,865 --> 01:27:43,649
I mean, that's
a pretty giant mouth.

2215
01:27:43,693 --> 01:27:45,172
[laughs]

2216
01:27:45,216 --> 01:27:47,436
- Is that megalodon
out there in the sea?

2217
01:27:47,479 --> 01:27:50,221
You know, 80% of the sea
hasn't been explored.

2218
01:27:50,265 --> 01:27:53,268
And every day, you see
new creatures popping up.

2219
01:27:53,311 --> 01:27:55,574
So perhaps someday,
the megalodon

2220
01:27:55,618 --> 01:27:57,272
is coming back to us.

2221
01:27:57,315 --> 01:28:03,060
- Megalodons went extinct
370 million years ago.

2222
01:28:03,103 --> 01:28:08,979
And, in my opinion,
I can't imagine

2223
01:28:09,022 --> 01:28:12,852
any way whatsoever that there's
still any in existence today.

2224
01:28:15,377 --> 01:28:19,206
- In the 70s, "Jaws" is
what, like, irked everybody,

2225
01:28:19,250 --> 01:28:21,644
because it was
confusing people

2226
01:28:21,687 --> 01:28:23,254
on what sharks
were really like.

2227
01:28:23,298 --> 01:28:26,779
And I think nowadays, it's
that megalodon mockumentary

2228
01:28:26,823 --> 01:28:29,042
that really irks scientists.

2229
01:28:29,086 --> 01:28:32,568
Because it's the idea
of being--of people being

2230
01:28:32,611 --> 01:28:36,311
tricked into thinking that
there's something out there

2231
01:28:36,354 --> 01:28:38,443
that's not really there
and that

2232
01:28:38,487 --> 01:28:41,577
it could encourage
current negative behavior.

2233
01:28:41,620 --> 01:28:43,535
It did what "Jaws" did
by accident.

2234
01:28:43,579 --> 01:28:47,104
"Jaws" accidentally convinced
people something was real.

2235
01:28:47,147 --> 01:28:51,369
And "The Meg"
mockumentary was trying

2236
01:28:51,413 --> 01:28:53,240
to get people to think

2237
01:28:53,284 --> 01:28:55,852
that something
that wasn't real could be.

2238
01:28:55,895 --> 01:28:57,157
- They aired this show,

2239
01:28:57,201 --> 01:28:58,855
"Megalodon:
The Monster Shark Lives,"

2240
01:28:58,898 --> 01:29:01,379
that claimed that
megalodon is not extinct

2241
01:29:01,423 --> 01:29:03,773
and it's still out there
and it's an active threat

2242
01:29:03,816 --> 01:29:05,340
to you and your family,

2243
01:29:05,383 --> 01:29:06,384
and scientists know that,

2244
01:29:06,428 --> 01:29:07,472
and the government knows that,

2245
01:29:07,516 --> 01:29:08,952
and they're lying to you.

2246
01:29:08,995 --> 01:29:10,519
Don't trust scientists
and the government.

2247
01:29:10,562 --> 01:29:13,348
I have spoken to thousands
of people all over the world,

2248
01:29:13,391 --> 01:29:15,045
giving these public talks

2249
01:29:15,088 --> 01:29:16,481
about sharks
and shark conservation.

2250
01:29:16,525 --> 01:29:18,004
I can't remember
the last time someone

2251
01:29:18,048 --> 01:29:19,397
didn't ask me about megalodon.

2252
01:29:19,441 --> 01:29:23,880
This is--Shark Week
just absolutely broke

2253
01:29:23,923 --> 01:29:26,143
public trust with this.

2254
01:29:26,186 --> 01:29:29,451
- I think that a lot
of shark scientists

2255
01:29:29,494 --> 01:29:32,410
and deep-sea scientists get
really angry with something

2256
01:29:32,454 --> 01:29:36,371
like "The Meg" is because
of all this intrigue and people

2257
01:29:36,414 --> 01:29:37,807
getting passionate
and maybe wanting

2258
01:29:37,850 --> 01:29:39,417
to do something with that.

2259
01:29:39,461 --> 01:29:41,767
And people like that are
really important,

2260
01:29:41,811 --> 01:29:43,856
especially
for ocean conservation,

2261
01:29:43,900 --> 01:29:45,467
so it's like you're
seeing this person

2262
01:29:45,510 --> 01:29:47,556
that you need on your team
for real ocean stuff,

2263
01:29:47,599 --> 01:29:49,427
and you're like,
"No, don't go chase mermaids.

2264
01:29:49,471 --> 01:29:51,342
"We need you to help
with like, the manatees

2265
01:29:51,386 --> 01:29:52,735
"that are actually stuck
right now

2266
01:29:52,778 --> 01:29:55,607
in some sort of climate change
thing in Florida."

2267
01:29:55,651 --> 01:29:57,087
Or like, "No, we need
you for the vaquita.

2268
01:29:57,130 --> 01:29:58,567
The vaquita is,
like, a real animal."

2269
01:29:58,610 --> 01:30:01,483
And instead it's like,
"No, we need to get a mission

2270
01:30:01,526 --> 01:30:03,789
to, like, find the meg
that's in the deep sea,"

2271
01:30:03,833 --> 01:30:05,095
which, it's not.
It's just gone.

2272
01:30:05,138 --> 01:30:06,792
It's extinct.
It's super extinct.

2273
01:30:08,620 --> 01:30:10,013
Even if something's extinct,

2274
01:30:10,056 --> 01:30:11,754
we want to believe
it's still around.

2275
01:30:11,797 --> 01:30:13,364
That's the appeal
of "Jurassic Park,"

2276
01:30:13,408 --> 01:30:16,106
right, is that there's
this mysterious element

2277
01:30:16,149 --> 01:30:18,543
or thing in the world
that we might be able

2278
01:30:18,587 --> 01:30:20,197
to control or discover.

2279
01:30:20,240 --> 01:30:21,764
And we like
to discover things.

2280
01:30:21,807 --> 01:30:24,070
It's part of humanity.

2281
01:30:24,114 --> 01:30:26,682
I think that sharks
become monstrous

2282
01:30:26,725 --> 01:30:28,640
because they do seem so alien.

2283
01:30:28,684 --> 01:30:31,164
Unlike a lot
of other predator creatures

2284
01:30:31,208 --> 01:30:36,387
that we have in our world,
sharks are largely unseen.

2285
01:30:36,431 --> 01:30:38,389
Anything that you've seen
in a movie

2286
01:30:38,433 --> 01:30:40,043
is the tip of the iceberg.

2287
01:30:40,086 --> 01:30:42,611
And what's real about sharks
in the ocean

2288
01:30:42,654 --> 01:30:45,962
almost always is
so much cooler.

2289
01:30:46,005 --> 01:30:48,573
What exactly steered me
into marine biology

2290
01:30:48,617 --> 01:30:52,534
was a very specific incident
with a great white shark.

2291
01:30:52,577 --> 01:30:54,884
And so that was
on a fishing boat.

2292
01:30:54,927 --> 01:30:58,017
I was about to win
the jackpot of the boat,

2293
01:30:58,061 --> 01:30:59,671
which is, like,
a really big deal.

2294
01:30:59,715 --> 01:31:03,196
The jackpot on a fishing boat
is the biggest fish.

2295
01:31:03,240 --> 01:31:05,677
And it was five days with me
and a bunch of dudes.

2296
01:31:05,721 --> 01:31:08,071
And so, like, I thought I was
gonna have this, like--

2297
01:31:08,114 --> 01:31:10,160
like, independent lady moment.

2298
01:31:10,203 --> 01:31:11,335
But then they yelled shark.

2299
01:31:11,378 --> 01:31:12,728
So a shark came over.

2300
01:31:12,771 --> 01:31:13,816
It was a great white.

2301
01:31:13,859 --> 01:31:17,254
It took my super large tuna.

2302
01:31:17,297 --> 01:31:20,736
It came by just like--I would
compare it to, like, Pac-Man.

2303
01:31:20,779 --> 01:31:22,694
It didn't look
like it had looked in a movie,

2304
01:31:22,738 --> 01:31:24,522
where it's like just all
"Jaws" and, you know,

2305
01:31:24,566 --> 01:31:25,871
moving around a bunch.

2306
01:31:25,915 --> 01:31:27,743
Long story short:
bring up the fishing line.

2307
01:31:27,786 --> 01:31:30,136
And what I have
is just a tuna head.

2308
01:31:30,180 --> 01:31:31,964
What had just happened
to the tuna

2309
01:31:32,008 --> 01:31:34,924
was the shark had bitten it
so efficiently

2310
01:31:34,967 --> 01:31:38,101
that its neurons
were still operating.

2311
01:31:38,144 --> 01:31:40,320
And so what I was looking at
was a head

2312
01:31:40,364 --> 01:31:41,974
that was still gasping for air.

2313
01:31:42,018 --> 01:31:43,976
And I thought it was
the coolest fucking thing

2314
01:31:44,020 --> 01:31:45,412
I'd ever see.

2315
01:31:45,456 --> 01:31:49,547
Because here this shark
had done the thing

2316
01:31:49,591 --> 01:31:52,594
that sharks do on TV or movie,

2317
01:31:52,637 --> 01:31:55,597
which is they kind of, like,
scare you and impress you

2318
01:31:55,640 --> 01:31:56,859
at the same time.

2319
01:31:56,902 --> 01:31:58,556
And here, the shark
had done exactly that,

2320
01:31:58,600 --> 01:32:01,080
but without doing
all the action

2321
01:32:01,124 --> 01:32:02,342
you see in a scary movie.

2322
01:32:02,386 --> 01:32:04,214
- The first time
I saw a great white,

2323
01:32:04,257 --> 01:32:05,650
you know, in the wild for real,

2324
01:32:05,694 --> 01:32:09,262
for me, it was as if
I had just met Marlon Brando.

2325
01:32:09,306 --> 01:32:10,568
That's the way I felt like.

2326
01:32:10,612 --> 01:32:13,136
Because, you know,
your whole life,

2327
01:32:13,179 --> 01:32:14,398
you read about great whites.

2328
01:32:14,441 --> 01:32:15,399
You read about sharks.

2329
01:32:15,442 --> 01:32:16,487
You watch shark movies.

2330
01:32:16,531 --> 01:32:17,488
You watch shark documentaries.

2331
01:32:17,532 --> 01:32:19,055
You see "Jaws."

2332
01:32:19,098 --> 01:32:22,101
So, like, this creature is
built up so much in your mind.

2333
01:32:22,145 --> 01:32:24,756
And so to actually see it was
like, to me, like, you know,

2334
01:32:24,800 --> 01:32:26,018
meeting a Hollywood celebrity.

2335
01:32:26,062 --> 01:32:27,280
It was amazing.

2336
01:32:27,324 --> 01:32:30,240
- When I spent four days
filming sharks

2337
01:32:30,283 --> 01:32:32,677
down in South Australia,
I was surrounded

2338
01:32:32,721 --> 01:32:34,113
by great whites for four days.

2339
01:32:34,157 --> 01:32:36,159
And you know, everything
I saw of their behavior

2340
01:32:36,202 --> 01:32:38,074
was just insanely wonderful.

2341
01:32:38,117 --> 01:32:40,729
I love and really do
respect sharks.

2342
01:32:40,772 --> 01:32:42,687
You know, I live
by the sea and I'm a surfer.

2343
01:32:42,731 --> 01:32:44,428
And I'm in the sea
every second day.

2344
01:32:44,471 --> 01:32:47,605
So for me, sharks,
it's their domain.

2345
01:32:47,649 --> 01:32:49,128
We're just visitors.

2346
01:32:49,172 --> 01:32:50,826
They've got every right
to do what they do there.

2347
01:32:50,869 --> 01:32:53,089
It's not like they're being
malicious or horrible.

2348
01:32:53,132 --> 01:32:54,569
That's just what a shark does.

2349
01:32:54,612 --> 01:32:56,309
If he--you know, occasionally,
there's a shark attack,

2350
01:32:56,353 --> 01:33:00,270
it's because it thought it
could eat you and stay alive.

2351
01:33:00,313 --> 01:33:01,401
- We just don't look
like anything

2352
01:33:01,445 --> 01:33:03,055
that they would want to eat.

2353
01:33:03,099 --> 01:33:06,624
If you looked at a table,
and you had a hamburger on it,

2354
01:33:06,668 --> 01:33:10,410
an onion, a salt shaker,
a bowl of flowers,

2355
01:33:10,454 --> 01:33:13,109
and a pitcher of water,
what are you gonna go for?

2356
01:33:13,152 --> 01:33:14,327
You go for the hamburger.

2357
01:33:14,371 --> 01:33:15,938
And we're the pitcher
of water.

2358
01:33:15,981 --> 01:33:17,156
You know,
we're just not something

2359
01:33:17,200 --> 01:33:18,680
they're gonna eat.

2360
01:33:18,723 --> 01:33:20,769
But if we aren't paying
attention to what we're doing

2361
01:33:20,812 --> 01:33:23,641
and we reach down on the table
and we grab the onion,

2362
01:33:23,685 --> 01:33:25,034
we might think it's an apple.

2363
01:33:25,077 --> 01:33:27,210
And we'd pick it up
and take a bite and go, oh.

2364
01:33:27,253 --> 01:33:29,691
Spit it out and go,
that's the wrong thing.

2365
01:33:29,734 --> 01:33:32,171
That's what I think happens
most of the time

2366
01:33:32,215 --> 01:33:34,609
when people are bitten
by sharks.

2367
01:33:34,652 --> 01:33:37,089
- Whenever we tend
to demonize something--

2368
01:33:37,133 --> 01:33:40,049
if that's a human,
or an inanimate object,

2369
01:33:40,092 --> 01:33:41,311
or an animal--

2370
01:33:41,354 --> 01:33:42,660
it's from a lack
of understanding.

2371
01:33:42,704 --> 01:33:46,359
- Peter Benchley used to say
we love our demons.

2372
01:33:46,403 --> 01:33:50,799
[chuckles] And sharks
represent iconically, I think,

2373
01:33:50,842 --> 01:33:52,670
a kind of a demon-y thing.

2374
01:33:52,714 --> 01:33:56,674
Sharks are not demons,
but they are dangerous.

2375
01:33:56,718 --> 01:33:59,155
And when you go
into their wild environment--

2376
01:33:59,198 --> 01:34:01,461
when you go into any animal's
wild environment--

2377
01:34:01,505 --> 01:34:05,030
you've gotta respect
the rules of that environment.

2378
01:34:05,074 --> 01:34:09,818
- We absolutely must have
sharks in the ocean.

2379
01:34:09,861 --> 01:34:12,559
We need our apex predators,

2380
01:34:12,603 --> 01:34:15,040
'cause they keep the balance
in the ocean.

2381
01:34:15,084 --> 01:34:17,826
And if you don't have them,

2382
01:34:17,869 --> 01:34:20,829
the balance gets
all out of whack.

2383
01:34:20,872 --> 01:34:25,224
It's like having the Serengeti
in Africa

2384
01:34:25,268 --> 01:34:26,878
without lions.

2385
01:34:26,922 --> 01:34:28,750
You've got to have the lions

2386
01:34:28,793 --> 01:34:31,274
to keep populations intact

2387
01:34:31,317 --> 01:34:35,017
and keep that ecosystem healthy
and thriving.

2388
01:34:35,060 --> 01:34:39,935
So apex predators, sharks,
are absolutely essential.

2389
01:34:39,978 --> 01:34:42,415
And there are 500 species.

2390
01:34:42,459 --> 01:34:45,244
Don't forget there are others
besides great white sharks.

2391
01:34:45,288 --> 01:34:46,985
- I call, like,
great white sharks,

2392
01:34:47,029 --> 01:34:48,204
like, a gateway drug,

2393
01:34:48,247 --> 01:34:49,684
but like,
they're a gateway shark,

2394
01:34:49,727 --> 01:34:51,468
because, for the people
that are really interested

2395
01:34:51,511 --> 01:34:52,774
in that stuff,
it, like, sucks them

2396
01:34:52,817 --> 01:34:54,514
into the whole world of it.

2397
01:34:54,558 --> 01:34:56,647
There's, like, all these
ridiculous shark movies,

2398
01:34:56,691 --> 01:34:58,649
and they come up
with all these ridiculous ways

2399
01:34:58,693 --> 01:34:59,955
to make the sharks scary,

2400
01:34:59,998 --> 01:35:02,000
and here's these real sharks

2401
01:35:02,044 --> 01:35:04,089
that already do things

2402
01:35:04,133 --> 01:35:06,135
that are a great plot
for a scary movie.

2403
01:35:06,178 --> 01:35:09,616
The ninja lanternshark
is jet black--

2404
01:35:09,660 --> 01:35:11,662
just very, very, very,
very dark black.

2405
01:35:11,706 --> 01:35:14,404
And all the lanternsharks
are glowing

2406
01:35:14,447 --> 01:35:16,232
as an invisibility cloak.

2407
01:35:16,275 --> 01:35:19,670
They're glowing just enough
to hide their shadows.

2408
01:35:19,714 --> 01:35:22,368
So basically,
this shark just wants to hide

2409
01:35:22,412 --> 01:35:24,153
before it gets you.

2410
01:35:24,196 --> 01:35:27,722
When it came to the end
of the project,

2411
01:35:27,765 --> 01:35:29,506
okay, we know this is
a real animal.

2412
01:35:29,549 --> 01:35:31,116
We know that we can get
this published.

2413
01:35:31,160 --> 01:35:32,465
Now we need to give it a name.

2414
01:35:32,509 --> 01:35:33,945
At the time of the publication,
it was gonna be

2415
01:35:33,989 --> 01:35:37,470
the 40th anniversary of "Jaws."

2416
01:35:37,514 --> 01:35:40,256
And we thought it'd
be really cool to use

2417
01:35:40,299 --> 01:35:42,345
this whole concept
of the "Jaws" effect

2418
01:35:42,388 --> 01:35:44,782
and this obsession with "Jaws."

2419
01:35:44,826 --> 01:35:47,045
And then the other cool thing
was to name it

2420
01:35:47,089 --> 01:35:48,917
after Peter Benchley.

2421
01:35:48,960 --> 01:35:51,658
So the common name
of the shark

2422
01:35:51,702 --> 01:35:53,443
is ninja lanternshark.

2423
01:35:53,486 --> 01:35:57,577
And then the scientific name
isEtmopterus benchleyi.

2424
01:35:57,621 --> 01:35:59,710
The genus isEtmopterus.

2425
01:35:59,754 --> 01:36:03,888
And then specifically, it's
named after Peter Benchley.

2426
01:36:03,932 --> 01:36:06,717
And so the way
taxonomic names go is,

2427
01:36:06,761 --> 01:36:09,633
if it's named after a male,
you add an "I."

2428
01:36:09,676 --> 01:36:13,376
So that's why the name is
Etmopterus benchleyi.

2429
01:36:13,419 --> 01:36:14,856
People would
probably think, like,

2430
01:36:14,899 --> 01:36:16,466
"Oh, it's the anniversary,

2431
01:36:16,509 --> 01:36:19,861
and oh, it's because,
you know, 'Jaws' is so cool."

2432
01:36:19,904 --> 01:36:23,386
But in my feeling,
it was to recognize

2433
01:36:23,429 --> 01:36:26,476
all this wonderful work
that the Benchley family

2434
01:36:26,519 --> 01:36:30,088
has done for ocean work
that no one would think about.

2435
01:36:30,132 --> 01:36:34,484
- Right after "Jaws"
and the huge success,

2436
01:36:34,527 --> 01:36:36,529
Peter was asked to do

2437
01:36:36,573 --> 01:36:40,446
many National Geographic
expeditions,

2438
01:36:40,490 --> 01:36:43,275
ABC sportsman expeditions.

2439
01:36:43,319 --> 01:36:46,931
And we very quickly
began to see

2440
01:36:46,975 --> 01:36:48,977
the destruction of the ocean.

2441
01:36:49,020 --> 01:36:52,284
We began to see
sharks being finned.

2442
01:36:52,328 --> 01:36:53,808
So as this happened,

2443
01:36:53,851 --> 01:36:56,245
Peter was being interviewed
more and more

2444
01:36:56,288 --> 01:36:59,422
and said, from his heart,

2445
01:36:59,465 --> 01:37:03,034
"There is no way I could write
'Jaws' now,

2446
01:37:03,078 --> 01:37:06,864
"because I know too much
about the ocean

2447
01:37:06,908 --> 01:37:09,780
and about great white sharks
and sharks in general."

2448
01:37:09,824 --> 01:37:13,044
So we started
to work hard at trying

2449
01:37:13,088 --> 01:37:15,307
to spread
the correct information,

2450
01:37:15,351 --> 01:37:17,570
that sharks need
to be preserved.

2451
01:37:17,614 --> 01:37:21,139
And please, please, please
don't think that because "Jaws"

2452
01:37:21,183 --> 01:37:25,709
was a novel and the movie
is fiction,

2453
01:37:25,752 --> 01:37:28,277
that this is somehow real life.

2454
01:37:28,320 --> 01:37:29,931
- Peter noticed
that I was getting

2455
01:37:29,974 --> 01:37:31,497
into conservation work.

2456
01:37:31,541 --> 01:37:34,457
And he said, "I want to do
something meaningful."

2457
01:37:34,500 --> 01:37:36,938
So we made--

2458
01:37:36,981 --> 01:37:38,548
I don't know,
it's about a dozen films.

2459
01:37:38,591 --> 01:37:41,029
We called them the "World
of Water Film Series."

2460
01:37:41,072 --> 01:37:46,643
And he and I did that
for the last part of his life.

2461
01:37:46,686 --> 01:37:48,993
And then I got
a phone call from Wendy.

2462
01:37:49,037 --> 01:37:51,561
And she told me he passed.

2463
01:37:51,604 --> 01:37:54,825
And she was crying,
I was crying, you know,

2464
01:37:54,869 --> 01:37:58,394
and she said, "And you know,
Greg, Peter always felt

2465
01:37:58,437 --> 01:37:59,830
"the work that he did with you

2466
01:37:59,874 --> 01:38:02,833
was the most important work
of his life, you know."

2467
01:38:02,877 --> 01:38:06,228
And it wasn't, by any means,
financially the most important,

2468
01:38:06,271 --> 01:38:07,838
nor was it the most popular.

2469
01:38:07,882 --> 01:38:09,971
It was just
the most meaningful.

2470
01:38:10,014 --> 01:38:14,149
- I think Peter would be
thrilled to know nowadays

2471
01:38:14,192 --> 01:38:17,195
how much interest there is
in sharks,

2472
01:38:17,239 --> 01:38:19,589
how much research has
been done,

2473
01:38:19,632 --> 01:38:22,766
that the world understands now

2474
01:38:22,809 --> 01:38:24,637
how important sharks are.

2475
01:38:24,681 --> 01:38:26,901
And there are many, many
environmental groups

2476
01:38:26,944 --> 01:38:28,424
working on this issue.

2477
01:38:28,467 --> 01:38:33,124
So we've come a long way
in almost 50 years

2478
01:38:33,168 --> 01:38:34,560
since he wrote "Jaws."

2479
01:38:34,604 --> 01:38:38,825
And I hope that within
the next ten years,

2480
01:38:38,869 --> 01:38:43,221
we really make more progress
on protecting sharks,

2481
01:38:43,265 --> 01:38:45,876
on marine-protected areas,

2482
01:38:45,920 --> 01:38:49,401
and on not overfishing
the ocean.

2483
01:38:49,445 --> 01:38:53,362
And you know, what happens is,
if you protect the ocean,

2484
01:38:53,405 --> 01:38:57,018
it has amazing ability
to just come back again.

2485
01:38:57,061 --> 01:39:01,370
And Peter worked really hard
on this all of his life.

2486
01:39:01,413 --> 01:39:04,982
And he always said,
"I'm gonna use 'Jaws'

2487
01:39:05,026 --> 01:39:08,116
"for all it's worth to bring
attention to the ocean

2488
01:39:08,159 --> 01:39:11,075
and to the issues
of conservation."

2489
01:39:11,119 --> 01:39:15,123
And so I've continued
with that thought in mind.

2490
01:39:15,166 --> 01:39:18,256
♪

2491
01:39:18,300 --> 01:39:19,997
- After we watched
a shark movie,

2492
01:39:20,041 --> 01:39:22,217
we also have a responsibility
to think

2493
01:39:22,260 --> 01:39:24,480
about how sharks are portrayed

2494
01:39:24,523 --> 01:39:26,438
and how you are talking
about sharks.

2495
01:39:26,482 --> 01:39:28,005
Yeah, it's a fun movie.

2496
01:39:28,049 --> 01:39:30,486
But the shark is actually
not a dangerous animal.

2497
01:39:30,529 --> 01:39:34,490
And we have a responsibility
to tell that story also.

2498
01:39:34,533 --> 01:39:35,970
- I know that in my research--

2499
01:39:36,013 --> 01:39:37,493
and I'm sure you've talked
to people

2500
01:39:37,536 --> 01:39:40,278
whose careers were inspired
by seeing "Jurassic Park"

2501
01:39:40,322 --> 01:39:41,976
or watching "Jaws."

2502
01:39:42,019 --> 01:39:43,760
- I saw Matt Hooper.

2503
01:39:43,803 --> 01:39:45,892
They could have put him
in a white lab coat

2504
01:39:45,936 --> 01:39:48,112
with a pencil holder
and notebook,

2505
01:39:48,156 --> 01:39:49,984
but instead, he had jeans,

2506
01:39:50,027 --> 01:39:52,290
he had a beard,
he liked to drink wine,

2507
01:39:52,334 --> 01:39:53,813
he told good jokes.

2508
01:39:53,857 --> 01:39:55,380
- Arguing with a man who's
lining up to be a hot lunch.

2509
01:39:55,424 --> 01:39:57,382
- That's why I think
a lot of oceanographers

2510
01:39:57,426 --> 01:39:58,557
look a bit like me.

2511
01:39:58,601 --> 01:40:00,777
That was the effect
"Jaws" had on me.

2512
01:40:00,820 --> 01:40:03,954
It was--it didn't scare me
out of the ocean.

2513
01:40:03,998 --> 01:40:06,043
It made me want to be
Matt Hooper.

2514
01:40:06,087 --> 01:40:09,003
- Over the years, that shark
became a character...

2515
01:40:09,046 --> 01:40:10,004
- Well, hi.

2516
01:40:10,047 --> 01:40:11,135
- That people loved.

2517
01:40:11,179 --> 01:40:12,615
- Name's Bruce.

2518
01:40:12,658 --> 01:40:15,096
- And people still keep
showing "Jaws."

2519
01:40:15,139 --> 01:40:18,099
I mean, I saw "Jaws" a couple
months ago at the Orpheum.

2520
01:40:18,142 --> 01:40:19,839
They had
over 1,400 people there

2521
01:40:19,883 --> 01:40:22,059
to pay $20 to see this movie

2522
01:40:22,103 --> 01:40:24,018
that's been around
for 40-some years.

2523
01:40:24,061 --> 01:40:26,890
- I think sharksploitation
will never die.

2524
01:40:26,933 --> 01:40:31,634
I think they will continue
to exploit every possible sub,

2525
01:40:31,677 --> 01:40:34,550
sub, sub-basement,
sublevel genre

2526
01:40:34,593 --> 01:40:37,161
of this particular realm
of films.

2527
01:40:37,205 --> 01:40:40,077
- What I'm seeing now
is almost like a renaissance

2528
01:40:40,121 --> 01:40:42,645
where there's, like,
this really cool potential

2529
01:40:42,688 --> 01:40:45,952
to entertain people
with science and facts

2530
01:40:45,996 --> 01:40:48,999
but make it totally
ridiculous at the same time.

2531
01:40:49,043 --> 01:40:51,175
- We've made sharks less scary.

2532
01:40:51,219 --> 01:40:53,264
Again, you know, it's--

2533
01:40:53,308 --> 01:40:57,268
I don't know if we should be
respected for that or reviled.

2534
01:40:57,312 --> 01:40:58,574
- Just give me
that great white,

2535
01:40:58,617 --> 01:41:00,141
let me eat my popcorn,

2536
01:41:00,184 --> 01:41:03,492
let me see it doing
some great white stuff.

2537
01:41:03,535 --> 01:41:08,410
- I'm a fan
of this exaggerated, campy,

2538
01:41:08,453 --> 01:41:12,066
kind of horror sci-fi
where it's very implausible,

2539
01:41:12,109 --> 01:41:13,763
but that doesn't mean
we can't enjoy it.

2540
01:41:13,806 --> 01:41:15,112
And I think that's
the important thing

2541
01:41:15,156 --> 01:41:17,593
with looking at any kind
of horror film

2542
01:41:17,636 --> 01:41:20,639
or any kind of film that paints
a real person or real animal,

2543
01:41:20,683 --> 01:41:23,251
like a shark,
as being a monster

2544
01:41:23,294 --> 01:41:24,948
or being evil
in some capacity,

2545
01:41:24,991 --> 01:41:28,517
is if we approach it as fun,
as an exaggeration,

2546
01:41:28,560 --> 01:41:30,127
and not as reality,

2547
01:41:30,171 --> 01:41:32,086
I think that we can still
appreciate it.

2548
01:41:32,129 --> 01:41:34,914
♪

2549
01:41:34,958 --> 01:41:35,959
[shark roaring]
